<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Presses Japan for Fair Access to Japanese Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union (EU), expressed serious
concern to the Japanese government today over its failure to
remove obstacles to the way container vessels dock, load and
unload at Japanese ports.
</P>
<P>
Foreign and domestic shipping lines now need prior approval,
even for small changes to their schedules, from the Japan Harbor
Transport Association (JHTA), a monopoly body running stevedoring
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The EU maintains that this practice can cause major disruption
and additional costs, given the high price of a day's loading and
unloading.
</P>
<P>
The EU has long been urging the Japanese government to reform
the so-called "prior consultation system" of the JHTA.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Japanese government promised to improve the
practice by July, but according to the EU, progress has been slow.
</P>
<P>
The United States also shares EU concerns. Its Federal
Maritime Commission has now imposed sanctions on Japanese shipping
lines.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, stevedoring companies are organized through the
JHTA, a body established under the auspices of the Ministry of
Transport. The prior consultation system gives the JHTA effective
monopoly control over all loading and unloading of ships in
Japanese harbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
