<HEADLINE> China's Last Old Provincial Airport to be Closed Tonight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- An outmoded airport at
Yinchuan, the capital of China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
will close at midnight Saturday and be replaced by a modern one
that can handle 600,000 passengers annually.
</P>
<P>
The New Hedong Airport will open tomorrow, Cheng Yu, deputy
director of the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC)
Ningxia Bureau, announced here today.
</P>
<P>
"Closing the Yinchuan Civil Aviation Airport marks the
beginning of modernization of China's civil aviation sector," said
Shen Yuankang, deputy director of CAAC.
</P>
<P>
The new airport cost 538 million yuan (65 million US
dollars). Construction work started in 1995. It is expected to
have more than 30 flights each week.
</P>
<P>
Officials accused the decade-old airport of blocking economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
"Ningxia has established about 400 joint-venture and solely
foreign-funded enterprises, compared with only a dozen in the
early 1990s," said Ren Qixing, vice chairman of the autonomous
region.
</P>
<P>
A record 18.4 billion yuan has been put into civil aviation by
governments of the backward northwestern provinces this year,
according to CAAC.
</P>
<P>
"I'm glad to see the airports in northwest China becoming more
and more advanced," said Swiss businessman Walter Bruggmann, who
was among the passengers aboard the last aircraft leaving the old
airport this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
More foreigners will come here to invest as local facilities
are improved, Yuning Wang, president of Canada's Richi Petroleum
Corporation, said before boarding.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
