<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Urges Japan to Honor Its Promise on Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, meeting
today with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, urged Japan
to respect China's stance on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Jiang reiterated the Chinese government stand that Taiwan is an
inalienable part of Chinese territory and that the Taiwan issue is
China's internal affair that no other country has the right to
interfere in.
</P>
<P>
He said the Japanese government has political obligations and
made a solemn promise on the issue of Taiwan in the China-Japan
Joint Statement and the China-Japan Treaty of Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons, any Japanese action related to Taiwan
would affect the feelings of the Chinese people, Jiang said, and
China hopes that Japan will respect the Chinese position on this
and act cautiously.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said Japan does not support "two Chinas", nor does it
support Taiwan independence. Japan holds that Taiwan, as part of
China, is not qualified at all to enter the United Nations, and
his government's stand on this is clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Japanese government, Hashimoto invited Jiang
for a state visit to Japan next year, which will be the 20th
anniversary of the China-Japan Treaty of Peace and
Friendship. Jiang thanked him for the invitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
