<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Tells PNA: No Anti-terror Fighting, No Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- In further reaction to
Thursday's bombings in Jerusalem, Israel decided today to freeze
the scheduled redeployments in the West Bank before the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) acts to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after an emergency Cabinet security
meeting convened by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Israeli
government condemned the PNA for failing to fulfill its main
commitment under the Oslo Agreement to combat terrorism and
terror infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Israel once again demands that the Palestinian Authority keep
all its commitments under the agreement," the statement said,
adding that the cabinet decided to stop handing over more land to
the PNA as long as it failed to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Netanyahu said, "We can't have a
situation in which we are asked to hand over more land to the
Palestinian Authority at a time when they are not fighting terror."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu once again lashed out at PNA President Yasser Arafat
for being responsible for the Thursday's bombings in central
Jerusalem's Ben Yehuda pedestrian mall, in which seven people
including three suicide bombers were killed and 190 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) claimed
responsibility for the attack and threatened to have more.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu accused Arafat of appeasing the terrorists by
kissing and embracing leaders of militant groups, including
Hamas, in recent meetings held in Gaza and Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet statement vowed that Israel "will act against the
terrorist organizations and their infrastructure to ensure the
security of its citizens and their fight to self-defense,"
implying that it might send troops back into the Palestinian
areas to hunt suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Following the July 30 twin bombing in Jerusalem's Mahane
Yehuda market which killed 17 people and was also claimed by
Hamas, Israeli government already approved to send troops to
enter Palestinian areas if necessary to hunt terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh said that Israeli security
forces would act independently, "without any connection to the
Palestinian Authority concerning everything to do with terror
organizations."
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who strongly condemned the Thursday bombing, maintained
that the suicide bombers came from abroad and not from the
territories.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the Thursday attack, Israel immediately
reimposed a total closure of West Bank and Gaza Strip, including
an internal travel ban on Palestinian residents in West Bank
cities.
</P>
<P>
Under the Note for Record attached to the Hebron Agreement
signed in January by Israel and the PNA under the auspices of the
United States, Israel should have completed the second phase of
troop pullout in the West Bank by September 7.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel has failed to implement even the first
redeployment, scheduled before March 7, because of the refusal by
the PNA to accept the 9 percent scope of pullout set unilaterally
by Israel. The PNA demanded Israel withdraw from 30 percent of the
West Bank in the first phase.
</P>
<P>
The PNA hopes to gain over 80 percent of the land after
Israel completes all the three stages of further pullouts in
the West Bank, on which it will establish an independent
state. But Israel is only willing to hand over about 40
percent of West Bank after the three-stage redeployments, which
were scheduled to be ended by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision to freeze further redeployments in fact
halted the Oslo process, which has already been questioned by many
in view of the huge gap and lack of trust between the two sides in
the wake of a series of terror attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
