<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outbreak of Meningitis in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Three people have died and 12
other cases of suspected meningococcal meningitis have been
reported in Zimbabwe's second largest city of Bulawayo.
</P>
<P>
The ministry of health and child welfare today issued a health
warning in the press alerting the public of an outbreak of
meningococcal meningitis which it said had the potential to
spread.
</P>
<P>
Acting director of disease and epidemiology control Batsirayi
Makunike said the cases were confined to Bulawayo only.
</P>
<P>
She said, "the disease is characterised by sudden onset with
fever, intense headaches, nausea and vomiting, stiff neck,
painful joints, a red rush and skin patches. Coma and confusion
may set in later."
</P>
<P>
She added, "meningococcal meningitis is easily spread in
overcrowded places. The disease is spreading by droplet
inhalation through the respiratory system. The disease spreads
very quickly and has a high death rate if left untreated.''
</P>
<P>
She said, "the ministry of health and child welfare and city
health services department in conjunction with WHO (World Health
Organisation) are doing their utmost to contain the outbreak."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Clear up Illicit Fee Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China's State Planning
Commission has suggested ways to use the Communist Party Central
Committee and the State Council's decision on stopping illicit
fees, fines, and other charges against enterprises.
</P>
<P>
One of the suggestions is for cancelling administrative
operating charges on enterprises, except for those stipulated by
state laws and regulations and in the documents of the State
Council, the State Planning commission and the governments at
provincial level.
</P>
<P>
Fees that conform to current regulations should be made clear,
and appropriate fees kept, merging redundant ones, and lowering
surcharges.
</P>
<P>
Management fees, especially for mediary services and management
fees in monopolies should be cleared up and standardized.
</P>
<P>
The SPC also suggested that government at all levels stop
approving new charges or raising the current ones for enterprises,
and that they be strict with rectification procedures in clearing
up current fees.
</P>
<P>
And they should crack down on any illicit fees, the SPC
stressed, saying that it will issue further regulations on
clearing up the collection of funds from enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
