<HEADLINE> NATO Chief to Visit Sarajevo Before Bosnian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Javier Solana, Secretary
General of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), is to
visit Sarajevo on the eve of the September 13-14 Bosnian municipal
election.
</P>
<P>
A NATO spokesman today disclosed the visit date and the
reinforcement of the NATO-led SFOR troops in Bosnia-Herzegovina,
from 31,000 to 39,000. Of the total, 3,000 will be stationed in
neighboring Croatia.
</P>
<P>
SFOR troops are being equipped with such anti-riot police tools
as batons, shields, dye-bombs and non-lethal grenades.
</P>
<P>
In another development, six F-16 jet fighters will fly from
NATO's Spandahlem base in Germany to Italy to join the 12 F-16s
already there for flights or aerial observation over Bosnia during
the coming election, the NATO spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,500 international observers will also be in Bosnia
for the election in 16 municipalities which is part of the Dayton
peace accord signed in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
"NATO would only resort to forceful means as a last resort and
if the situation so requires," said a NATO source.
</P>
<P>
Both Solana and NATO Supreme Commander General Wesley Clark
have made it clear that SFOR troops would not tolerate any
attacks on them. 
</P>
