<HEADLINE> Car Sales Hit All Time High in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Car sales in Britain reached a
record high in August with 8 billion U.S. dollars worth of new
cars sold out.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released today by the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders (SMMT), 525,539 cars were sold, an
increase of 9.62% over the same period last year when 479,945 cars
were registered.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that windfall payments from building societies,
a surge in home prices, and the return of the "feel-good" factor
helped to send sales to the record.
</P>
<P>
But the extraordinary one-month sales also brought a huge boost
for foreign manufacturers, with seven in ten cars registered
imported during August.
</P>
<P>
Of the total August sales, 357,769 cars came from abroad.
Half of the top ten best-sellers came from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Ernie Thompson, chief executive of SMMT said the August
achievement "is a milestone figure and represents a huge volume of
business for the industry."
</P>
<P>
"But it demonstrates clearly the absurdity of having more than
25% of annual registrations in just one month," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Confederation of British Industry (CBI) has urged the Bank
of England not to raise interest rates further despite figures
showing that car sales broke all records last month.
</P>
<P>
Ian McAllister, chairman of Ford, the market leader, insisted
the figures did not reflect an overheating economy or an
unsustainable consumer boom, saying "my gut feeling is that the
economy is not as strong as these figures suggest". 
</P>
</TEXT>
