<HEADLINE> Pakistan Wants Good Relations with Neighbors: Leghari </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari said here today that his country wants good relations with
its neighbors and desires peaceful resolution of all outstanding
issues including the core issue of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Leghari made the remarks while meeting with Rick Inderfurth,
the new assistant secretary of state for South Asia, who arrived
here Thursday on a visit to Pakistan as a part of his five-nation
tour of the region.
</P>
<P>
The president exchanged views with his guest on a wide range of
issues including Pak-U.S. bilateral relations and the situation in
the region, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Explaining Pakistan's position on the issue of Jammu and
Kashmir, Leghari reiterated that Pakistan seeks a just and
peaceful resolution of the issue through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Leghari expressed the confidence that the Pak-U.S.
relations would continue to be improved.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan was looking forward with keen interest to
the visit of U.S. Secretary of State Albright to Pakistan this
year and the proposed visit of President Clinton to the region
next year.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the Brown Amendment permitting the transfer of
defense equipment purchased by Pakistan had set the stage for
opening a new chapter in U.S.-Pakistan relations, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan and the United States share common
objectives and interests on most issues, particularly in the
desire to seek peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan supports the United Nations' efforts at bringing about
a durable peace in Afghanistan, Leghari said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Pakistan was pursuing a policy of
non-interference in the internal affairs of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts are directed towards cessation of hostilities, and
the formation of a broad based and representative government," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth informed Leghari about the deep interest of the
United States in peace and stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country supports the process of dialogue which
has begun between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States believes that the situation in
Afghanistan is a source of instability in the region and would
like to see it to be resolved, Inderfurth said.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth's five-nation "familiarization tour", which started
from India, will also take him to Bangladesh, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
