<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Unemployment Rate Up to 4.9 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate
increased to 4.9 percent in August as new jobs were created at the
slowest pace in nearly a year, U.S. Labor Department reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The gain of the jobless rate resulted partly from the UPS
strike which had a big impact on job growth. UPS temporarily
subtracted 164,000 jobs from the economy, although the U.S. Postal
Service and other competitors increased hiring by 9,000 to pick up
some of the slack.
</P>
<P>
The report said that crosscurrents left net job growth at
49,000 in August, the worst showing since September 1996. However,
that followed an extremely strong gain of 365,000 jobs in July,
revised up from an earlier estimate of 316,000 and it represented
the biggest gain in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
It showed that the manufacturing sector added a striking 47,000
jobs last month, the most since February 1990.
</P>
<P>
Job growth in retailing increased by 31,000 following two
strong months. The finance industry continued to add workers, with
11,000 in August, bringing growth over the past 26 months to
nearly 200,000. Construction employment rose by 10,000 jobs, the
first gain since May.
</P>
<P>
Government jobs increased by 72,000, bolstered by postal
service hiring and teachers returning to school.
</P>
<P>
The report said that average workweek rose 0.2 hours in August,
to 34.7 hours, after a 0.1-hour decline the month before.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly earning also increased by 5 cents last month to
a seasonally adjusted 12.29 dollars, compared with 1 cent increase
in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Europe's Security Opens in Vilnius </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VILNIUS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international
conference on European peaceful coexistence opened today in the
Lithuania's capital Vilnius.
</P>
<P>
The conference named "Coexistence of Nations and Good
Neighbourly Relations -- the Guarantee of Security and Stability
in Europe," were initiated by presidents of Lithuania and Poland
Algirdas Brazauskas and Alexander Kwasniewski.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Belarus, Estonia, Latvia, Ukraine, Bulgaria,
Hungary, Finland, Moldavia, Romania and Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin, attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed that after the cold war, peace and
development have become a main trend of the world, where security
and stability are the key of the trend. All the countries of the
world should make every effort to create a peaceful and stable
international environment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the international
conference, Brazauskas said "By gathering in Vilnius, we will have
an opportunity to seek new ways of implementation and practical
application of the principles of democracy, co-operation, security
and good neighbourly relations enshrined in the Helsinki final act
and other international documents."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the states of Central and Eastern Europe which in
this century suffered extremely painful blows of history, hold a
special role and responsibility in preventing a repeat of old
mistakes and, instead, by concerted joint efforts, overcoming the
current problems for the free, secure and prosperous Europe.
</P>
<P>
Brazauskas emphasized the task facing heads of state is to
create such an environment in the region which would bring people
closer to each other and become a reliable barrier against
incitement of animosity between them.
</P>
<P>
On the European security, Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko said that "Europe seems to be missing a historic chance
to create a common family of nations and peoples enjoying equal
rights."
</P>
<P>
He described the decision on the expansion of NATO to the east
as a "crucial mistake".
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko noted that "We ought to do everything possible to
minimize the negative consequences of this erroneous step and not
to allow the coming back of animosity and suspicion in
relationship between our nations and people."
</P>
<P>
He also said that nothing unites people more than a common
activity and economic interests. Therefore, the European states
should pay special attention to the discussion on regional and
economic cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said "a foundation for new
relations between the States is being laid and the shape of the
future European structure is being determined."
</P>
<P>
He said European states have got a unique chance at present to
make the Baltic Sea, Central Europe and the Black Sea region one
of the generators of peace and cooperation in the entire Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia sees the establishment of a new model of the
Baltic-Black Sea cooperation as an integral component of a new
Europe, said Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
The conference is also attended by the representatives of the
European Commission and the Council of Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
