<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Civil Service Numbers Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The downward trend in Civil
Service staff numbers in Britain has continued, said Cabinet
Office here today.
</P>
<P>
Between 1 April 1997 and 1 July 1997 the number of permanent
civil servants fell by one percent or 3,200 to 472,000, four
percent less than a year earlier, according to a press release by
the Office.
</P>
<P>
The number of casual staff increased in the second quarter by
300 or one percent to 19,000, nine percent fewer than 12 months
earlier, reflecting the continued use of casual staff to overcome
fluctuations in workload and short-term shortages of permanent
staff.
</P>
<P>
Taking both permanent and casual staff into account the trend
has continued downward, the overall total having fallen from
495,000 on 1 April to 492,000 on 1 July.
</P>
<P>
Since the peak in 1976 the number of permanent staff has fallen
37 percent from 751,000 to 472,000. Casual staff numbers have
increased by 79 percent over the same period, from 11,100 to
19,900.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Office said the largest reductions in numbers of
permanent staff in the three months till 1 July occurred in the
Ministry of Defense (2,270 down), the Benefits Agency (920 down),
the Department for Education and Employment (620 down) and the
Department of Trade and Industry (610 down).
</P>
<P>
The largest increases in numbers of permanent staff in the same
period were in the Prison Service (530 up) and the Scottish
Prison Service (310 up), in response to the increasing prison
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
