<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Georgia's Economic Reform Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of 65 million U.S. dollars in financing to
support the economic reform program in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The financing consists of a 60 million dollar equivalent Second
Structural Adjustment Credit (SAC II) and a 5 million dollar
equivalent Second Structural Adjustment Technical Assistance
Credit (SATAC II) to the country.
</P>
<P>
The SAC II will be used for consolidating the stabilization
gains recently achieved and strengthen the current economic
recovery. The SATAC II is designed to enhance the capacity of the
Georgian Government to carry out the structural reform program
supported by the SAC II.
</P>
<P>
Both credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries, on standard IDA terms with a
maturity of 35 years, including a 10 year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Since joining the World Bank in 1992 and IDA in 1993, Georgia
has benefited from World Bank and IDA commitments totaling some
345 million dollars for 13 projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
