<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Circular On Medical Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- China's State Council has
issued a circular on reforming the medical storage and supply
sector to better prepare the nation for disasters, epidemics, and
other emergencies.
</P>
<P>
It says that there will be a system of central supplies for
serious disasters and local ones for lesser disasters.
</P>
<P>
The State Council and provincial level governments should
ensure funds for the central and local medical supply, it said,
and the State Pharmaceutical Administration and departments at the
provincial level should improve the administration of medical
supplies for greater efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The State Council says it will oversee the State Economic and
Trade Commission, the Ministry of Supervision, the State
Pharmaceutical Administration, and other departments'
implementation of the circular's demands.
</P>
<P>
A Xinhua News Agency commentary today said that the current
medical supply system, which was established in the 1970s, can no
longer meet the needs of the new nation.
</P>
<P>
The circular provides ways of improving the national medical
supply system, it said, and pointed to advantages for unified
policy, planning and implementation, and the role of central and
local governments the reform will bring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting On Improving Commercial Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A meeting has been held in
the capital of China's Henan province to discuss establishing
commercial centers in some pilot cities in central and western
China.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized by the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy (SCRE), the State Planning Commission,
the State Economic and Trade Commission, the Ministry of Internal
Trade, and the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Co-operation. In 1994 these offices started a project for this by
designating Lanzhou, Zhengzhou and Chengdu as pilot cities.
</P>
<P>
The project was described at the meeting as "a correct choice
for economic development of central and western China", and it is
considered significant for the reforms and opening-up
</P>
<P>
Shao Bingren, vice-minister in charge of the SCRE, said that
establishing commercial centers is more than merely reforming the
commercial sector, and can only succeed by reforming the whole
economic structure.
</P>
<P>
In putting commerce at the center of the service sector, Shao
said, pilot cities should also use more overseas investment
combined with the readjustment of industry and enterprise
structures.
</P>
<P>
He called for unified leadership and effective co-ordination
for the project, which in his words is a "complex systems
engineering."  
</P>
</TEXT>
