<HEADLINE> Worlddidac Keen On China's Educational Equipment Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Beat Jost, executive director
of Worlddidac Association, said today that China Didac '97 has
attracted 50 foreign investors in the educational equipment
industry, and many more are interested in China's large market.
</P>
<P>
"With a population of 1.2 billion, accounting for one fifth of
the world's total, education has experienced a prosperous era in
recent years thanks to efforts made by the Chinese government and
educators," he said.
</P>
<P>
China Educational Instrument and Equipment Corporation (CEIEC),
the organizer of China Didac '97, has provided a chance for
foreign traders to learn more about the country's education
system, development, school equipment, and teaching equipment, he
said, and it will promote trade exchanges and technological
co-operation between Chinese manufacturers and foreign businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Worlddidac is a trade and sales association for education
publications and equipment, with 350 members in 45 countries. It
helped China host an international education equipment, material
and instrument exhibition in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Matsushita Electronic Industrial Co. Ltd. carried out China's
first educational cooperation project with CEIEC to develop
language lab equipment in early 1980s, Jost said.
</P>
<P>
The two parties have had a lot of similar projects, including
the largest Sino-Japanese language lab equipment joint-venture, in
Suzhou, in Jiangsu province, he said, and the first-phase of
construction involved 30 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Investors from 50 countries have set up over 1,000 co-operation
projects with Chinese companies and school-run enterprises in
education materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Britain, and the United States have shown strong
interest in investing or co-operating with Chinese manufacturers
in the sector during the four-day exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottwy Beats Jones in Tokyo Athletics Internationa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jamaican sprinter Merlene Ottey
beat world champion Marion Jones of the United States to win the
women's 100m race at the Tokyo international athletics tournament
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ottey, who finished a disappointing seventh
after a false start in the world championships, made a perfect
start this time to clock 10.83 seconds, beating the 21-year-old
American by eight hundredths of a second.
</P>
<P>
World silver medallist Zhanna Pintusevich of Ukraine, who
narrowly lost the world title to Jones in a photo finish final in
Athens last month, came in third in 11.16.
</P>
<P>
Pintusevich, who won the 200m gold medal in Athens, was also
beaten earlier in her favourite distance when American Inger
Miller clocked 22.77 to beat her into second by 0.10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Donovan Bailey could manage only second in his
last race of the season, beaten by Frankie Fredericks of Namibia,
who clocked 10.04 to repeat his performance here last year,
beating the Canadian by 0.14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Six-time world champion Sergei Bubka of Ukraine failed to clear
6.16m mark in an attempt for his 36th world record, but
comfortably won the men's pole vault with a 5.80m jump, far better
than American runner-up Dean Starkey's 5.65.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 3,000m steeplechase, Denmark's Kenyan-born Wilson
Boit Kipketer gained some consolation when the former world record
holder clocked 8:19.80 to beat Bernard Barmasai by four hundredths
of a second.
</P>
<P>
It was a repeat performance for 23-year-old Kipketer, the world
800m record holder, who defeated the same opponent into third to
win the world championships.
</P>
<P>
After Athens, Kipketer established an old world mark of 7:59.08
on August 13, only to see Barmasai break it again 11 days later at
the Cologne Grand Prix in Germany with a time of 7:55.72. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
