<HEADLINE> Hong Kong UNICEF Committee Makes Donation To Chinese Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Committee for
UNICEF today donated 1.2 million US dollars to the Chinese
government for neonatal tetanus vaccinations and for increasing
the study opportunities for girls living in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador of the United Nation's Children's Fund Leon Lai, a
well-known Hong Kong singer, handed the donation for the two
projects to the UNICEF China Area Representative Keshab B. Mathema
at a news conference in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Mathema said that the HK Committee for UNICEF has
transfered about 3.5 million US dollars to UNICEF China for
procuring oral polio vaccine since 1994. In 1996, it donated
disaster-relief goods, worth 250,000 US dollars, to quake-stricken
Yunnan province.
</P>
<P>
He said that Leon Lai performed at two benefit concerts in Hong
Kong that raised over 300,000 US dollars for the polio campaign in
China, since he was designated as UNICEF Ambassador in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In August, lai raised 200,000 US dollars through a charity
bazaar in Hong Kong to help girls in China's poor areas attend
school, he said.
</P>
<P>
Poor areas have the highest incidence of neonatal tetanus, and
need financial aid, according to a Chinese Health Ministry
official.  
