<HEADLINE> Diana's Funeral Held in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The funeral of Britain's
Princess Diana was held Saturday morning in London's Westminster
Abbey, with millions of mourners bidding farewell to "the People's
Princess".
</P>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth II, Diana's former husband Prince Charles, her
sons Princes William and Harry, and other members of the royal
family and Diana's family joined the 1,900 people attending the
funeral service inside the abbey.
</P>
<P>
Celebrities and political leaders, including British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, former United States secretary of state,
Henry Kissenger, and former British prime minister, Lady Thatcher,
mingled with ordinary people in the abbey to pay their respects.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the morning, Diana's coffin, draped in the royal
standard and crowned with three sprays of white flowers, was
carried out of her London home, Kensington Palace, to Westminster
Abbey on a gun carriage. Millions of mourners lining the streets
watched silently as the cortege passed.
</P>
<P>
Princes Charles, William and Harry, along with Diana's brother
Earl Charles Spencer, and the Queen's husband Prince Philip were
in the funeral cortege.
</P>
<P>
Five hundred people who worked for or were helped by the 110
charities linked to Diana also joined the cortege on its way to
the abbey.
</P>
<P>
After an emotional speech by Tony Blair, singer Elton John,
Diana's close friend, sang the song, "Candle in the Wind", which
described Diana as a candle that burned out long before her legend
ever would.
</P>
<P>
While paying a personal tribute to his sister Diana during the
funeral service, Spencer delivered a bitter attack on the media,
blaming the press for hounding Diana to death.
</P>
<P>
The funeral ended with a one-minute silence across the
country. Diana's coffin was then driven to her family home in
Althorp, central England, for burial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
