<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues political Restructuring (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese theorists say that
China's political restructuring is not a kind of reform to
"destroy the present system or demolish the basic framework", but
will proceed in an orderly fashion.
</P>
<P>
"No big change will take place in the general pattern of
China's political structure," Wang Jiaqiu, vice-president of the
Party School of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central
Committee, predicts. This echoes what President Jiang Zemin said
in a speech on May 29 at the Party School about the need for
continuing the reform of China's political structure.
</P>
<P>
However, Wang said, this does not mean that political
restructuring will have to destroy the present system or tear down
the basic framework, but it should be carried out in a step by
step manner.
</P>
<P>
Wang explained that political restructuring is not something
abstract. When there have been breakthroughs in economic reforms,
the political structure must fit the reforms and special attention
should be paid to the introduction of a legal system and
increasing democracy gradually.
</P>
<P>
"The market economy should not be ruled by man, but by law,"
she emphasized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Comoros' Stop to Armed Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- France today welcomed the
decision by the Comoran government to stop armed operation in the
separatist island of Anjouan, after heavy casualties were
reportedly inflicted upon government forces who landed on the
island Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
France also promised to provide emergency humanitarian help to
those on both sides of the conflict who became victims of the
fighting over the past three days in Anjouan, said a communique
issued by the French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
``France has constantly stressed that the present problem in
the Comoros could not be solved by the resort to force and had
deeply deplored the fightings and the casualties caused by this
operation,'' said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Comoros said the military operation in
Anjouan, launched by the Comoran government despite opposition
from the Organization of African Unity (OAU), had resulted in the
death of 40 government soldiers and 18 civilians.
</P>
<P>
The envoy of the OAU to the Comoros, Pierre Yere, said the
operation had resulted in a ``debacle''.
</P>
<P>
The island of Anjouan, one of the three islands that make up
the Indian Ocean nation, declared ``independence'' on August 3 and
asked for the return of French rule, which was withdrawn in 1975.
</P>
<P>
France appealed to all parties in the conflict to cooperate
with the OAU to seek a political and consensual solution and to
respect ``the cohesion, unity and territorial integrity of the
Islamic Federal Republic of the Comoros,'' said the communique.
</P>
<P>
``We reiterate our total support to the project of the OAU to
organize as rapidly as possible an inter-Comoran conference this
summer,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the French Foreign Ministry, a non-governmental
humanitarian group is launching a rescue operation in Anjouan to
help the people victimized by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
``In the immediate (future), France is ready to provide
emergency rescues needed in the island of Anjouan... to help those
who have been the victims on both sides,'' said the communique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Political Restructuring (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li says that China's political restructuring has been carried
out in such a cautious and steady way that the political reform
has been mistaken for "lagging behind".
</P>
<P>
Experts say that historic changes have quietly taken place in
China's political life while its economic reforms have been
carried out on a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
The results of political restructuring in the past five years
are improving the following: the people's congress system, the
multi-party co-operation system and the political consultative
system under the leadership of the CPC, the personnel system,
establishing a legal framework for a socialist market economy,
cracking down on corruption and building a clean government, and
guarantees of citizens' democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
These changes have resulted in a steady and progressive
political restructuring, they say.
</P>
<P>
Political observers say that China has quickened the pace of
legislation in the past few years, and one fundamental step is
that people's congresses at various levels have been playing an
increasingly greater role in the country's political life.
</P>
<P>
More than a third of the 300 laws and decisions adopted or
revised in the past two decades have come since 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Political Restructuring (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature,
and its Standing Committee have a final say in the nation's
general and specific policies and in appointing major government
officials. Its annual section has become an important place for
deputies from across the country to exercise their power.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Xiaoyang, deputy director of the Commission of Legislative
Affairs of the NPC Standing Committee, says that laws on every
aspect of China's political, economic and social life have been
passed and a socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics
has been instituted, based on the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China has also made progress in reforming
administrations and that institutional restructuring has taken
place across the nation since the Second Plenum of the 14th CPC
Central Committee in February, 1993.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the 68 ministries, commissions and offices
directly under the State Council, China's highest governing body,
have been cut to 59, and government offices at the provincial
level have been cut by some 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Personnel Ministry, the central government
departments have selected more than 1,700 civil servants through
examinations in the past four years, and governments at the
provincial level have hired 190,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Political Restructuring (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A fair and competitive system for choosing government officials
has been formed.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that there are still major obstacles to institutional
restructuring, particularly in the definition of duties, which
involves a change of work style and way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
Institutional restructuring and the definition of duties are
expected to be a major part of political restructuring after the
CPC 15th National Congress, which begins September 12.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Civil Affairs official says that village
committee democracy in rural areas has also attracted a great deal
of attention. The direct election of village committees by secret
ballot has become a common practice in many places.
</P>
<P>
Since Village Committee Organic Law took effect in 1978,
several rounds of elections have been held in provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities, and the fourth round of
elections took place this year in Shanxi, Hebei, Fujian and
Heilongjiang provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Village committee leaders used to be appointed by the local
government but today, farmers enjoy the right to nominate them,"
the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
