<HEADLINE> 49 Civilians Massacred Near Algerian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Forty-nine civilians were
massacred and about 60 injured Friday night, presumably by Islamic
extremists, in Beni Messous near the Algerian capital Algiers,
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that an armed commando of Islamic militants
descended on the village of Sidi Youssef and slaughtered the
villagers with axes and other agricultural tools.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the mutilated bodies of the victims were
assembled on the ground of a hospital in Beni Messous.
</P>
<P>
This is the worst massacre to have taken place near the
Algerian capital since Algeria was plunged into violence in 1992
after the army cancelled an election victory won by Islamists.
</P>
<P>
About 300 people were massacred last Friday in Reis 20
kilometers south of Algiers by extremists in the worst massacre of
civilians in five years.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government early this week rejected an appeal by
the United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to seek a
political, rather than military, solution to the internal conflict
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said in a statement last weekend that the
Algerian conflict was no longer a purely internal problem, and the
international community would not see the Algerian people
abandoned to their fate.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Algeria said that Abassi Madani, the head of the
outlawed Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) who was recently released
from jail, will make an appeal for peace within 15 to 20
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
