<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Prime Minister Visits Museum in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto visited a museum for the "September 18 Incident"
this afternoon in the capital of northeast China's Liaoning
province.
</P>
<P>
On September 18, 1931 Japanese troops blew up a section of the
Dalian--Harbin Railway near Shenyang, then accused the Chinese
troops of sabotage as a pretext and bombarded the barracks of the
Chinese troops near Shenyang the same evening, thus starting
massive armed invasion against northeast china.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told a group of resporters at the museum that No
matter how forgetful people may be, they should not forget
history. They can learn from history, but must not change
history. They must bear the burden of history, he said.
</P>
<P>
He continued that he has come to Shenyang with the wish of
viewing history correctly, and that this could be a basis of
better Sino-Japanese relations and for casting our sights on the
future.
</P>
<P>
The museum has a 20-meter-high stone calendar scarred by
thousands of bullets. At the top are the characters for "September
18, 1931". It also has an exhibition hall with relics recording
the developments of the incident and how the Chinese army and
people fought back against Japanese aggression.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the visit, Hashimoto wrote on the visitors book:
"peace is what matters".  
</P>
</TEXT>
