<HEADLINE> Australian Defense Minister to Visit Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian Defense Minister
Ian McLachlan heads off to Japan tomorrow for a three-day visit,
the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled visit "marks the substantial change in the
security relationship underlined by the agreement in April between
Prime Minister John Howard and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto for an expansion of defense cooperation activities," the
AAP said.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said in a statement that his visit "is one of the
ways to show the importance which we place on our relationship
with Japan."
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the contribution to be made by defense to
the security dialogue which we have established will continue to
reinforce our shared security interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I also believe that we have a strong basis to carry forward
the further development of defense contacts... Australia and Japan
shared substantial security interests," said the defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Australia's defense links with Japan remain delicate because of
memories of World War II, AAP said. The Japanese launched armed
attack at Australia and some neighboring Pacific Island countries
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Mclachlan is scheduled to meet his Japanese counterpart Fumio
Kyuma, director-general of defense agency, Japanese Foreign
Minister Yukihiko Ikeda and other senior military officials,
according to AAP.
</P>
<P>
Australia has strengthened its military ties with the United
States over the past year, while the United States and Japan are
reviewing their security treaty.  
</P>
