<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Face Challenges of 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will face the
challenges of the 21st century through scientific and
technological means, including proper utilization of water and
other natural resources of the country, Water Resources Minister
said here today.
</P>
<P>
He made this statement at a workshop on "Ground water and
Environment" jointly organized by the Bangladesh Geology Society
and the Alumni Association of German Universities.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged the geological scientists to identify the
problems relating to the ground water and environment and find out
their solution for ongoing development of the country and
improvement of the life standard of the people.
</P>
<P>
He called upon them to work with devotion for developing the
ground water as they have contributed in the field of oil, gas and
coal sectors of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Government will take necessary steps for higher
education and research in the geology departments of the
universities to create technically sound manpower in the field,
the minister stated.
</P>
<P>
The government has fixed a target for producing 25 million
metric tones of food grains in the proposed Five-Year Plan and
more surface water will be required in irrigation, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are presently using 70 percent to 90 percent of water from
the ground water for irrigation and drinking purposes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Owing to huge unplanned uses of the ground water, the
environment of the country has been affected badly, the minister
noted, adding that most of the shallow tubewells for supplying
drinking water have become imperative as the ground water level
came down.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Bay areas of the country are now flooded by saline
water and, arsenic pollution is found at different areas of the
country owing to the unplanned uses of ground water, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
