<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE (MALAWI), September 6 (Xinhua) -- Refugees from
Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of Congo are expected to start
returning to their home countries this week, the local paper
Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Lucius Chikuni, a senior official
with the Malawian Ministry of Relief and Rehabilitation, as
saying in Lilongwe, capital of the country, that the government
has booked seats for those refugees willing to return to their
own home countries.
</P>
<P>
Of 64 Rwandans who were registered at Dzaleka Refugee Camp two
weeks ago, only 22 are willing to be repatriated, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said out of 116 Congolese refugees registered at the same
time, only 57 are willing to return home.
</P>
<P>
At least 680 Rwandan refugees fled the camp in central Malawi
before the registration. Many of them are believed to be soldiers
suspected of being implicated in genocide cases back home, said
the official.
</P>
<P>
"Many of them have returned to camp, the sole camp in the
country, after hearing that the repatriation is voluntary," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that there were 1,742 refugees in the camp at
the end of July this year. 
</P>
