<HEADLINE> Malawi's Tobacco Production Faces Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE (MALAWI), September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Tobacco
Association of Malawi (TAMA) is unlikely to recover its loans of
more than 250 million Kwacha (about 15 million U.S. Dollars)
given to growers earlier this year, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
It may spell doom to the future of the country's number one
crop, the local newspaper Nation said.
</P>
<P>
Sources from TAMA indicated that only 120 million Kwacha has
been recovered although over 75 percent of TAMA's 64,000 members
have already sold their tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The failure to pay back the loans is blamed on low prices and
also on cheating, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Some growers are deliberatedly avoiding selling their tobacco
at the auction floors where TAMA recovers its loans, preferring
to sell through middlemen or other outlets instead, a TAMA
official said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture blamed the low prices on the
incessant heavy rains this year which affected the quality of the
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The anti-smoking campaign in the United States has also
affected the export of Malawi tobacco to the United States, one
of the big buyers of the Malawi leaf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
