<HEADLINE> Redgrave Wins Sixth World Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Briton Steve Redgrave grabbed a
sixth world title to his personal credit when he led Britain to
victory in the men's coxless fours in Aiguebelette, France on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old Redgrave, who is aiming for a record fifth
Olympic title in Sydney at the 2000 Games, his former coxless
pairs partner Matthew Pinsent, Timothy Foster and James Bracknell
clocked a time of 5:52.44 to win the race.
</P>
<P>
The British coxless fours are unbeaten this season and Redgrave
himself has not lost a race since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Britain's women's coxless fours also won their final. Susan
Walker, Alexandra Beever, Elisabeth Henshilwood and Lisa Eyre beat
Romania and Germany with a time of 6:40.30.
</P>
<P>
Australia won the men's lightweight eight in a very tense
finish, beating Britain by just 0.03 seconds, with Canada taking
third place within a second.
</P>
<P>
The United States also snatched two gold medals thanks to Sarah
Garner in the women's lightweight single sculls and the coxed pair
of Scott Fentress and Jordan Irving.
</P>
<P>
Hosts France won the coxless pairs with Atlanta bronze
medallists Michel Andrieux and Jean-Christophe Rolland beating
Italy and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
