<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cairo to Host Urgent Tripartite Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- An urgent tripartite summit
grouping Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) will be held here tomorrow to discuss the worsening
situation in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, King Hussein of Jordan and
PNA President Yasser Arafat will discuss the latest developments
of the peace process and the measures taken by the Israeli
government against the Palestinian people and its government,
Mubarak's political adviser Osama el-Baz said today.
</P>
<P>
According to reports earlier, Arafat will fly to Egypt today
for talks with Mubarak in the aftermath of a triple suicide
bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will also address the tight Israeli closure of
Palestinian areas after Thursday's attack in a shopping mall
in Jerusalem, which killed eight people and wounded 192.
</P>
<P>
Israel has held the PNA "indirectly responsible" for the
attacks, the second in the city in five weeks, and reimposed a
complete closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip which had been
eased earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu ruled out handing over more
land to Palestinians Friday until Arafat cracked down on Muslim
militants, accusing him of failing to honor a commitment under
interim peace accords to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel has withdrawn its troops, handing over much of the Gaza
Strip and parts of the West Bank to Palestinian self-rule under
peace deals with Arafat starting in 1993. It is supposed to
withdraw from more of the West Bank by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Arafat condemned the latest attacks as "terrorist activities"
masterminded from abroad, but he swiftly denounced the Israeli
decision as destroying the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman said Israel was trying to obstruct the first
visit to the Mideast by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
scheduled to start this week.
</P>
<P>
Albright's multi-leg mission, which President Bill Clinton
confirmed on Thursday would go ahead, expected to revive the the
Palestinian-Israeli peacemaking that has been in crisis since
March over Jewish settlement construction in East Jerusalem the
Palestinians want as part of a future state.
</P>
<P>
The stalemate has been deepened by the suicide attacks, first
on July 30 when 15 Israelis were killed by two suicidal bombs in
a Jerusalem market and second on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Ambassador Praises China's Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Ambassador to China
Inamul Haque, speaking with Xinhua recently about China's policy
of peace, called it successful and said that although the Cold War
has come to an end, some countries continue their policy of
hegemony and power politics.
</P>
<P>
He said that China, has declared its opposition to these
policies and pursues a foreign policy based on the principles of
international law and norms governing state-to-state relations,
and respects sovereignty, territorial integrity, non-interference
in other countries' internal affairs, non-aggression, and the
peaceful settlement of disputes.
</P>
<P>
China is the only developing country with a permanent seat and
veto power in the Security Council of the United Nations, Haque
pointed out, and said: "Pakistan appreciates the role China plays
in the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"And we are confident that China will continue to safeguard its
own national interests as well as those of the developing
countries in the years ahead and will continue to respect and
implement UN decisions and resolutions", he added.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It is only in a climate of international peace that
members of the international community, particularly the
developing countries, can devote their energies to the essential
task of socio-economic development and improving well-being of
their people."
</P>
<P>
China has successfully withstood external political pressure
and has scored rapid economic development, he said, adding that it
has a traditional friendship with other developing countries and
supports them in their demand for a just and equitable
international economic order, and is providing assistance in funds
and technology to them.
</P>
<P>
He called Pakistan and China "old friends" that have stood by
each other in good times and bad, enjoying the best of relations
for the last five decades.
</P>
<P>
"Both Pakistan and China are fully committed to international
and regional peace and security and have closely co-operated with
each other at the UN and other international fora in all areas",
he noted.
</P>
<P>
He called these relations a model of inter-state relations
based on the fundamental principles of peaceful co-existence and
mutually beneficial economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said he is confident that these will continue to gather
strength and promote international peace and security and the
economic well-being of people all over the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
