<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The death of an icon: Mother Meresa, 1979 Nobel Peace Prize
winner and the most media-covered religious figure in the world,
died at 87 in Calcutta on Friday. Received everywhere by world
leaders, she was admired for her service for the miserable in the
slums of the Indian metropolitan, as well as for her lobby against
abortion on the planet.
</P>
<P>
-- The confrontation between Comoran troops and the separatists
of the island of Anjouan which began on Wednesday had resulted in
the death of at least 40 government soldiers and 18 civilians, said
Comoran opposition groups. The envoy of the Organization of African
Unity to the Comoros, Pierre Yere, also said the military operation
in Anjouan by government forces turned out to be a ``debacle''.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The funeral of the Princess of Diana held today in London
would be no doubt the funeral of the century, at least in a
democracy.
</P>
<P>
-- Christian Blanc, the head of Air France who tried in vain to
persuade Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to accept his proposal to
privatize the air company, decided on Friday to quit the presidency
of the company, which he took over in 1993 when it was in the depth
of a financial disaster. 
</P>
