<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Leaders of SADC Members to Attend Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE (Malawi), September 6 (Xinhua) -- All the 12 heads of
state from the Southern African Development Community (SADC) will
attend a summit to be held in Blantyre, Malawi on Monday,
according to the information desk of the SADC summit today.
</P>
<P>
All the regional leaders will arrive today, but Nelson
Mandela, President of South Africa might arrive a bit late, the
information desk said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is said to be in Europe with other engagement.
</P>
<P>
The SADC leaders will have a challenging task and the debate
which starts on Monday when they are to purify the image of the
southern Africa in the world, officials with the SADC said.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Nzo, chairman of SADC Council of Ministers, said that
remarkable progress has been made in the region over the past
years since the region's GDP has jumped to over six percent.
</P>
<P>
However, heads of the SADC member states will have a tough
assignment in the wake of yet another serious drought which will
hit the region in the next growing season.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of recurrent drought underscores the critical
importance of the role to be played by the newly created water
sector in conserving and harnessing the region's water
resources," Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
Nzo's warning against the approaching drought was hailed as
timely for the region.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit will discuss issues like the consideration of
draft protocols on education and mining.
</P>
<P>
The use of illict drugs is also to be tackled at the summit,
according to the SADC information desk.
</P>
<P>
The ban of production, distribution and use of anti-personnel
landmines will also be high on the agenda of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The applications of the Democratic Republic of Congo (former
Zaire), and Seychelles to join the group will be discussed at the
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
