<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Minister Expects Israeli Retaliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Minister of Information
Basim el-Sabaa today expected fresh Israeli attacks against
Lebanon to retaliate for its heavy losses in south Lebanon Friday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Cairo-based Voice of Arabs radio, the
minister said the failed Israeli raid in south of the Lebanese
port city of Sidon was meant to plant explosive charges in
Lebanese installations several kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
Some 12 Israeli soldiers were killed Friday in fighting with
Lebanese troops and guerrillas after an Israeli airborne commando
launched a pre-dawn raid on the village of Insariyeh, about 45
kilometers north of the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
This was the worst casualty for Israeli forces in a single
battle in the area since Israel set up the security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The heavy casualty raised fears of tough Israeli retaliation
that usually comes in the form of lightning air strikes on
Hezbollah targets in south Lebanon, the last active front line in
the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli pre-dawn raid, hours after a triple suicide
bombing in West Jerusalem, was meant to retaliate an Amal
attack last week in which five Israeli soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
On the first visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Sabaa said Lebanon was not officially notified
if Beirut will be included in her upcoming Mideast tour scheduled
to start this week.
</P>
<P>
If Beirut will be included, Sabaa said, talks with Albright
should focus on implementation of U.N. Security Council Resolution
425, which calls for immediate and unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from the Israeli self-proclaimed security zone in south
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
