<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Tap Human Resources Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), who are gathering here for
preparation of the group's Monday summit, have pledged that they
will tap the huge potential in human resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued here today said that the ministers
meeting which ended on Friday highlighted the governance and
poverty in their human resources discussions.
</P>
<P>
A SADC Region Human Development Reports Project (RHDRP) will
assist SADC member leaders to initially produce two advocacy
issues concerning human resources, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, SADC's Executive Secretary, will chair a
Steering Committee to provide overall leadership for the project.
</P>
<P>
Close consultation with the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) will be made to ensure overall management of the project.
</P>
<P>
The initial stage of the regional human development project
will be launched in July 1998, while the second phase is to start
in July 1999, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the project will outline the UNDP global
governance development framework.
</P>
<P>
The project is to be submitted to the SADC summit on Monday.
</P>
<P>
SADC is a sub-regional organization aimed at promoting
integration among its 12 members, including Angola, Botswana,
Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Republic of Congo (former Zaire), and
Seychelles have applied to join the southern African group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
