<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Launch Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has decided to launch a
free trade and industrial zone in Azzobair bay, Al-Basra
province, in southern Iraq, the Iraq News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision is part of the Iraqi efforts to revive its economy
and trade and minimize the effects of the embargo imposed by the
U.N. seven years ago for its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Director of the Iraqi General Customs
Authority (GCA) Hamid Shokr Mahmoud as saying that preparations
are underway for surveying and planning the area whose designs
envisage roads, parks, offices, service centers, communications,
fire fighting units, a medical center and a fuel station.
</P>
<P>
The zone will be connected, through land roads and railways,
to Arab, European, Asian and African states, thus reducing time
and the costs of transport and labor, Mahmoud added.
</P>
<P>
It will turn the area into an Arab and international trade
center for its distinguished geographical location to the north
of the Arab Gulf, the official said.
</P>
<P>
A resolution on the establishment of the free trade and
industrial zone in Azzobair was adopted by the Iraq cabinet on
May 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
