<HEADLINE> Science and Tech, Hong Kong's Competitive Edge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Science and technology has
played and will continue to play an increasingly important role in
 ensuring that Hong Kong remains a competitive manufacturing and
services center in the global market, a high-ranking official of
the Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a scientific conference, Acting Financial Secretary
Ki Chi Kwong said that the Hong Kong government is committed to
enhancing the development and application of science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has adopted a three-pronged approach to upgrade its
science and technology capacity, Kwong said in a keynote speech
entitled "Science and Technology Policy for the HKSAR".
</P>
<P>
The government first provides suitable physical infrastructural
facilities by, for instance, earmarking three industrial estates
and setting up technology centers. A science park is being
planned, added the official.
</P>
<P>
The second part of the government approach is to invest in
human resources and the third, to support research and development
activities.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, over the past three academic years,
Hong Kong has invested 31 billion HK dollars (nearly 4 billion
U.S. dollars) in tertiary education, of which 35 percent or 11
billion HK dollars (1.4 billion U.S. dollars) went to the
development of science and technology-related teaching and
research programs.
</P>
<P>
For academic research, a total of 540 million HK dollars (69
million U.S. dollars) has been granted between 1995 and 1998, more
than four times the figure between 1992 and 1995 -- 120 million HK
dollars (15 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the increased investment, the research base has
expanded and there has been a general move towards larger
projects, especially in medicine and engineering fields, Kwong
told scientists at the fifth Annual Scientific Conference and
General Meeting, organized by Hong Kong Institution of Science
(HKIS).
</P>
<P>
The HKIS, founded in 1992, has grown into an outstanding
society today with more than 300 members, including academics,
officials and figures from industrial circles.
</P>
<P>
Leroy L. Chang, president of the HKIS, said that the goal of
the HKIS is to promote science in Hong Kong, a significant job as
it has been widely recognized that the world depends increasingly
on science to advance technology for the benefit of society.
</P>
<P>
The most important activity of the HKIS is its annual
scientific conference and general meeting, which gathers members
and scientists for one-day discussions on the latest development
trend of science and technology, and its impact on social and
economic life.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
