<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rain Alert System for HK Schools Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Office of
Ombudsman has made a proposal to have a new rainstorm warning
system for local schools to be available, probably before next
year's rainy season, the office said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made by the Ombudsman after the
Education Department criticized the existing system as confusing
and problematic.
</P>
<P>
The department staff were heavily criticized by parents after
the department failed to close schools on the morning of June 4
despite severe flooding in some of the local areas.
</P>
<P>
At present, the warning system is based on actual rainfall
measurement, but the radical overhaul would rely on forecasts,
giving families time to prepare.
</P>
<P>
And when the red rainstorm signal was posted, kindergartens and
primary schools would be closed automatically.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department and individual schools currently have
to make their own decisions in the event of a red signal warning.
</P>
<P>
The black signal would close all schools, as under the present
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new system will be similar to the typhoon warning
system, which links the closing of offices to typhoon signals.
</P>
<P>
The watchdog recommended on the Hong Kong Observatory to
forecast when rainstorm warnings were likely to be issued.
</P>
<P>
But the Observatory said Friday that the Education Department
should make the final decision on whether schools should be
closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
