<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Forecasts Development Trend in 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific region,
with the world fastest growing pace, will emerge in the 21st
century as the most prosperous market and one of the manufacturing
and service centers in the globe, said a Chinese scientist here
today.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address at a scientific conference organized by
the Hong Kong Institution of Science (HKIS), Prof. Lu Yongxiang,
president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences listed a number of
reasons for his optimistic view of the economic development
prospects in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The speech was delivered by Prof. Leroy Chang, president of the
HKIS on behalf of Prof. Lu, who could not attend the one-day
conference, a forum for scientists to discuss the development
trend of science and technology, and related policies.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Lu said in his speech that one third of the world
population amass in the Asia-Pacific region, which has a huge
market and tremendous manpower resources. Cultural advantages,
well-established infrastructure, stable and peaceful environment,
a huge amount of capital and hefty foreign exchange reserves,
improved education and research, and world-wide technological
innovations will all contribute to the surge of the region.
</P>
<P>
With China's reform and open-up, a market economy and trade
liberalization have become the main stream in the region, Prof. Lu
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "The Prospects of Science, Technology and Education
into the 21st Century", the speech tries to explore the
development trend and characteristics of economy, science,
technology, and education in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
"The mankind will step into the age of the so-called Knowledge
Economy," said Prof. Lu, who predicted that technological
innovation is bound to bring about new industrial revolution,
change economic and consuming structures, and shape modes of
production and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
The next century will be a century of information, of life
science, and of new materials and advanced manufacturing
technique, according to the speech.
</P>
<P>
The world's economy will further demonstrate the feature of
globalization, science will go through profound changes from
linear disciplines to cross-disciplinary integration, and
education will be molding the future of the country and the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Also at the conference, Ki Chi Kwong, acting financial
secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
government delivered a keynote speech on the Hong Kong's science
and technology policies.
</P>
<P>
It is the fifth annual scientific conference organized by the
HKIS, which, founded in 1992, has now grown into an outstanding
society in Hong Kong. The HKIS has more than 300 members,
including academics, and figures from government and industrial
circles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
