<HEADLINE> Southern African Ministers Morn over Diana's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, (Malawi), September 6 (Xinhua) -- The 12-member
Southern African Development Community (SADC), of which 11 states
are Commonwealth members, paid a special respect to Princess
Diana whose funeral was held in London today.
</P>
<P>
SADC people shall always cherish the memory of Princess Diana
as a "true friend of southern Africa who passionately shared our
dream of a southern Africa free of the scourge of ani-personnel
landmines which have caused untold misery to millions of our
people," said Alfred Nzo, chairman of SADC Ministerial Council
and foreign minister of South Africa, at a press conference
today.
</P>
<P>
The memory of Princess Diana will "inspire the thoughts and
vision of southern Africa at peace with itself and the rest of
the world," Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
At the SADC ministers' conference, ministers of the southern
African sub-region, paid special honor to Diana, Princess of
Wales, whose high-profile involvement in the anti-landmine
campaign and global fight against AIDS has won praise worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Diana flew to Angola as part of a British Red Cross campaign
to ban the manufacture of land-mines in March.
</P>
<P>
In a country where the number of landmines seems to have
surpassed that of the population, and an estimated 70,000 of a
total of about 12 million Angolans have lost their limbs or
suffered other devastating effects of landmines, Diana's death
means a lot, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
Diana was planning to attend the internatinal conference
seeking a global ban on landmines which began in Oslo on
September 2.
</P>
<P>
Southern African leaders were urged to spare no effort to
attain the objective that Diana had fixed for herself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
