<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Grants Uganda 56 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has decided to grant Uganda 56 million U.S. dollars in
the first year of a three-year program under the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily The New Vision today, the grant
followed an agreement reached between a visiting IMF team that
visited Uganda from August 19 to September 4 and the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team came to conclude negotiations that began in May
for the ESAF program for the 1997/98 to 1999/2000 period. The
first annual arrangement of the program covers the fiscal year
1997/98. The agreement is subjected to approval by IMF management
and executive board.
</P>
<P>
Ulrike Wilson, IMF resident representative in Uganda was
quoted as saying that the IMF executive board is expected to meet
in November this year.
</P>
<P>
She said,"Once the program is approved the first of the two
disbursements for this year will be made. This will be 28 m
dollars. The second disbursement will come after the mid term
review. The mission to review the mid term performance comes in
February 1998."
</P>
<P>
Wilson said the three-year arrangement is for 75 percent of
Uganda's quota in the IMF.
</P>
<P>
She said this was equal to about 140 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The focus of the program this year is on revenue measures
because last year's revenue collection was significantly below
program budget. It turned out some important new measures had to
be put in place to strengthen revenue performance," Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
She said this would be done through improving in the way Uganda
revenue authority operates and through reforming customs
administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crew Return to Mir After Failing to Find Hole in Module </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Two cosmonauts returned to the
Russian Mir space station after a six-hour spacewalk today, during
which they failed to find the puncture in the Spektr scientific
module.
</P>
<P>
But the two men, Russian cosmonaut Anatoly Solovyov and NASA
astronaut Michael Foale, had partial success in repositioning a
key solar panel.
</P>
<P>
They were ordered by mission control to re-enter the Mir
station after they tried unsuccessfully in locating the puncture.
</P>
<P>
The gash, which depressurized the module, was caused on June 25
in a collision between a Progress cargo craft and the orbital
station.
</P>
<P>
The punctured module is now airless and one of its panels was
destroyed and the remaining three were disconnected by the crew
who fled it immediately.
</P>
<P>
Today's spacewalk started around 0100 GMT and the two
cosmonauts tried for more than five hours during the spacewalk to
locate the hole.
</P>
<P>
Several more spacewalks would be needed to find and repair the
puncture which depressurized the module, said Korolyov Mission
Control outside Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Ministers Urges for Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE (Malawi), September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Southern
African Development Community (SADC) foreign ministers have urged
that the sub-regional organization be integrated into a common
market.
</P>
<P>
SADC should be transformed into a "dynamic development
community" by an unswerving faith in the abilities of the people
in the region, said South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo,
chairman of the SADC Ministerial Council at a two-day ministerial
meeting which ended here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis should be put on stakeholder participation in
determining the content and priorities of SADC protocols, he
said, adding that the protocols to be submitted to the Monday
summit will provide the foundation for regional integration and
development.
</P>
<P>
The protocols are to define the modalities, procedures and
institutions that will guide the group's further cooperation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Education, mining, tourism and human resource development will
be forwarded to the summit for discussion, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit to be held here on Monday will discuss
plans for the African Economic Community to be materialized by
the year 2030.
</P>
<P>
Five new protocols on education, gender, industry, mining and
water are expected to be signed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The group summit will also find ways to bring peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional organization, mostly Commonwealth states,
will stress on closer economic ties within the sub-region, with
unified development policies, which will facilitate their
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Information exchange, enhancement of technological capacity,
common standards, environment protection, occupational health and
safety and the promotion of private sector participation will be
included in the protocols to be submitted to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit is to find ways to maintain a sustainable
development through tighter ties among the member states.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also search out ways to cooperate with other
economic and political organizations in Africa and other
international organizations, among them the Organization of
African Unity (OAU),the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) and European Union (EU), the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
SADC, which was established in August 1992, is aimed at
promoting economic integration towards a fully developed common
market.
</P>
<P>
The 12 SADC members are Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia,
Namibia and Zimbabwe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
