<HEADLINE> Kenyan Trade Team to Visit South-Eastern Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A strong team of Kenyan local
businessmen and trade officials will visit south-eastern Asia to
market Kenyan products and build business contacts, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
As many as 13 businessmen and officials from the Export
Processing Zones Authority (EPZA), Export Promotion Council and
the Ministry of Tourism and Wildlife will visit Hong Kong, Korea,
Malaysia, Singapore and Taiwan late this year.
</P>
<P>
EPZA Chief Executive Silas Ita said on Friday that these Asian
countries and regions are regarded by Kenya as potential outlets
for Kenyan products and sources of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan delegation will seek to identify opportunities for
joint ventures between Kenya and investors from the region, as
well as try to promote trade and tourism between Kenyan suppliers
and overseas buyers, said Ita.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is attractive due to tax incentives, preferential market
access to the region, competitive labor, unrestricted foreign
exchange regime and "deep and irreversible reforms", he said.
</P>
<P>
The target areas for investment are power, port, rail, roads,
telecommunications and water infrastructure. Other areas include
tourism, agri-business for export and domestic markets,
manufacturing and services.
</P>
<P>
The team will also target textile industries, motor vehicle
assembly, electronics, computer assembly and jewellery cutting,
said Ita. 
</P>
</TEXT>
