<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Soldiers Killed by Rebels in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- At least three government
soldiers were killed and two others injured in a fierce fighting
today with Tamil rebels in North Central province of Sri Lanka,
according to a military spokesman here.
</P>
<P>
Ink Dewage, the spokesman said around 7 a.m. today, a group of
rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) attacked a
patrol of government troops which was sent out Kandegam detachment
in Polonnaruwa district, 216 kilometers from Colombo.
</P>
<P>
He said that the troops repulsed the assault but at least three
soldiers died and two others wounded due to the rebels' attack.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war for a
separate Tamil state in the north and east of the island country
since 1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Positive on Results of China Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto said here today that his current visit to China
is "fruitful and of great significance."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference before ending his first Beijing
tour as Prime Minister, Hashimoto said that the visit is
significant because it takes place on the occasion of the 25th
anniversary of the normalization of Japan-China relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has held fruitful talks with President Jiang
Zemin, Premier Li Peng and other Chineses leaders during his stay
in Beijing. He said that they have changed views on a wide range
of issues, including bilateral relations, regional situation and
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He believes that the visit reinforced the political foundation
of bilateral relations and laid a foundation for forging a
Sino-Japanese relationship of trust and cooperation, which is
oriented to the next century.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that his current visit and other planned
exchange of visits between leaders of the two countries will
promote the healthy and stable development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the development of Sino-Japanese
relations in the past 25 years, he said that although the two
countries have totally different social systems, they have
stridden over these differences and been remaining friendly to
each other. Both sides have received benefits from their
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that today, China has become the second largest trade
partner of Japan, while Japan remains the largest trade partner of
China.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the two countries would make efforts
to enhance the level of their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question about Japan's view on the past,
Hashimoto reiterated the Japanese Government's formal stance on
this issue as the cabinet under former Prime Minister Tomiichi
Murayama made it public in 1995.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will be the first Japanese Prime Minister to
visit northeast China and the Museum of September 18th Incident in
1931 there since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said that his visit to that part of China is to show
Japan's willingness to correctly view the past and create a future
of friendly cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on whether the scope of Japan-US
security cooperation includes the Taiwan Straits, he said that the
Japanese Government fully understands and respects the Chinese
Government's position on Taiwan issue. He said that the Japanese
Government will strictly follow the principle embodied in the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement that Taiwan is an inseparable part
of China. He said that his country will act with caution and never
support "two Chinas" or Taiwan independence.
</P>
<P>
Later, Hashimoto and his entourage left Beijing for Shenyang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
