<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Two cosmonauts returned to the Russian Mir space
station after a six-hour spacewalk today, during which they failed
to find the puncture in the Spektr scientific module.
</P>
<P>
But the two men, Russian cosmonaut Anatoly Solovyov and NASA
astronaut Michael Foale, had partial success in repositioning a
key solar panel.
</P>
<P>
They were ordered by mission control to re-enter the Mir
station after they tried unsuccessfully in locating the puncture.
(Russia-Space-Mir)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- News of the death of Mother Teresa, widely hailed
as the embodiment of love and compassion, have plunged India into
sorrow and grief.
</P>
<P>
The Mother, 87, breathed her last after a heart attack at 9:30
p.m. (local time) on Friday in Calcutta, capital of India's West
Bengal state.
</P>
<P>
President Kocheril Raman Narayanan and Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral led the nation in mourning the death of one who for
long years had come to be regarded as a legend in her lifetime.
(India-Mother Teresa)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union (EU) Saturday warned the United
States against violating world trade obligations on
satellite-based services.
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive body, the European Commission, requested the
U.S. side to change the rules issued on July 16 which would block
foreign operator's access to direct-to-home services and digital
satellite services in the United States. (EU-US-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- Dwellers in Bangladesh's capital are suffering from an
acute shortage of water, the Water Supply and Sewerage Authorities
(WSSA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The water supply is about 40 percent short of the demand of the
ever growing population of the capital, it said.
</P>
<P>
The WSSA, an autonomous body responsible for operating the
sewerage system and supply of water in the metropolis, is now
supplying 860 million liters of water while the total requirement
is 1,350 million liters. (Bangladesh-Dhaka-Water Shortage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- The Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE) will send an additional team of 250 international
observers to supervise the forthcoming Bosnian Serb local
elections, according to an OSCE press release issued Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The observers will form groups of two each and travel across
the Serb-controlled areas to watch the elections while the 2,450
sent in earlier by the OSCE will do the same in
constituencies. (OSCE-Bosnia-Elections) 
</P>
