<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of the
crude palm oil (CPO), tin and rubber closed the week all higher.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the CPO physicals market was supported on
export news that the State Trading Corporation of India is buying
between 6,000 and 12,000 tons of RBD (Refined, Bleached and
Deodorized) palm olein for September 10-25 shipment.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Wong, a private forecaster said Friday that August's palm
oil production was expected to increase 2.4 percent to 853,000
tons and August's stock level will be about 870,000 tons, which is
well-above the market's forecast of 840,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
September south closed the week at 1,360 ringgit (about 468.96
U.S. dollars) per ton, 10 ringgit (3.44 dollars) higher against
1,350 ringgit (465.51 dollars) per ton recorded at last week's
close.
</P>
<P>
The CPO market is expected to improve further next week despite
the weak ringgit as the market sentiment is still on a bullish
note with the surrounding positive fundamentals prompting the
commodity to enjoy encouraging demand, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), the tin price, which
broke its 14-month high at 15.76 ringgit (5.43 dollars) per kg on
Thursday, ended the week nine sen higher at 15.66 ringgit (5.4
dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The metal continued to see the absence of Japanese traders who
shied away in view of the wide discount between the KLTM and the
London Metal Exchange (LME) while European and local buyers were
active players.
</P>
<P>
Turnover fell to 468 tons this week from 796 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to lose some ground next week as
profit-taking will continue to depress market sentiment, dealers
said, adding that a downside potential is there, given the fact
that the metal was currently fetching a high premium.
</P>
<P>
The performance of the LME, which staged a long-running rally
this week, will play an important role in determining the
market's direction next week, they said.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market this week, October RSS One
jumped 5.50 sen to 264.50 sen (about 91.2 U.S. cents) per kg while
SMR 20 leaped six sen to 262.00 sen (about 90.3 U.S. cents) per
kg.
</P>
<P>
Middle East, China, India and Morocco were the main buyers
throughout this week, especially for SMR 20 grades.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for September 4 was at 199.38
Malaysian/Singapore cents against 195.57 cents on August 28.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average widened to 199.48 cents from 193.93
cents last week.
</P>
<P>
The local rubber market is expected to remain range-bound next
week with prices hovering around the 260 sen (about 89.6 U.S.
cents) per kg level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
