<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Seek 2.1 Billion Dollar Aid for 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is likely to seek 2.1
billion U.S. dollars aid for the 1997-98 fiscal year, beginning
from July 1 this year, from the donors at the Aid Group meeting,
scheduled to be held here in early November, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the figures remained around two billion dollars in
the past several years, which means that the commitment of aid
depends on how much a country can absorb for its development,"
said a senior official of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that Dhaka would give priority to the construction
of the Ganges barrage, Rupsha bridge, Padma bridge, development of
the Mongla Port in its aid memorandum and will seek extended
amount of aid from the donors at the forthcoming Aid Group
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will also propose to form a consortium comprising
the donor countries and agencies to construct the Ganges Barrage,
which is regarded by Dhaka as the key project to develop its
flood-prone northwestern region.
</P>
<P>
But, according to the Finance Ministry official, if the donors
wish to provide funds for construction of the Ganges Barrage or
Rupsha bridge, they will provide funds in additional to the normal
level of aid, given every year.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second time that the World Bank will organize
the annual meeting of the Aid Group in Dhaka on November 4-5. The
first such kind of meeting was held in Dhaka in 1973, two years
after this South Asian country's independence.
</P>
<P>
Since then, all previous meetings of the Aid Group for
Bangladesh were held in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the year's Aid Group meeting will be followed by a
two-day investors' conference on November 6-7, which is likely to
be participated by 30 to 35 representatives from globally reputed
foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a large number of local investors will also take part
in the conference, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
