<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) fluctuated tremendously this week.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Composite Index rebounded to 840.42 points with
the return of local funds from the Independence day holiday
(September 1), but the index retreated to 675.15 two-days later on
persistent selling pressure by foreign investors who have been
able to deposit their shares with the Central Depository System
(CDS).
</P>
<P>
Local funds, in response to the call by Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad, aggressively bought up stocks on the
last day of trading this week, pushing the Index which tracks 100
quality stocks, to close the week at 821.59, or 17.19 points or
2.1 percent over last week's closing.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index gained 11.70 to 231.18, the Industrial Index
rose 38.35 points to 1,657.58 and the Second Board Index recouped
27.27 points to 401.01.
</P>
<P>
The re-entry of local funds in the market on the closing day
was a surprise, causing foreign players who have been selling
heavily "to let stocks run".
</P>
<P>
Many analysts said from now, the market should stabilize
although there is still a possibility of further selling pressure.
</P>
<P>
They said with Mahathir's announcement of the lifting of
designated securities status on 100 Composite Index components,
coupled with the deferment of some huge projects in view of the
current external imbalance and the weaker ringgit, were all
positive reasons which will be attributable to the market's
stability.
</P>
<P>
The local stock market's slide recently was attributed to local
players being enticed to sell by the exaggerated bad sentiment and
rumors and increased foreign selling.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index is expected to make a comeback technically
to the 836 and 880 level with resistance noted at between 890 and
910, or 38 percent level below the all time high level of 1,332.
</P>
<P>
"A breakout at between the 880 and 908 level will catapult it
to the 1,018 resistance level," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 actives included Renong (up 34 sen to 3.34 ringgit
with 73.125 million shares traded), Berjaya Group (up nine sen to
1.78 ringgit with 65.144 million shares), Commerce Asset (down 24
sen to 3.40 ringgit with 63.089 million shares), Sime Darby (down
20 sen to 6.70 ringgit with 45.907 million shares) and Malaysian
Resources (up 67 sen to 3.02 ringgit with 44.754 million shares).
</P>
<P>
The weekly main board volume increased to 1,802.990 million
shares valued at 7.0357 billion ringgit (about 2.4258 billion U.S.
dollars) from 1,584.554 million shares worth 6.2005 billion
ringgit (2.1381 billion dollars) a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover decreased to 167.200 million shares
valued at 1.3260 billion ringgit (457.263 million dollars) from
197.236 million shares worth 1.5750 billion ringgit (543.129
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total direct business transaction amounted to 165.428
million shares valued at 625.819 million ringgit (215.799 million
dollars) compared with 199.441 million shares worth 1.3153
billion ringgit (453.551 million dollars) last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
