<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mir Crew Fail to Locate Hole in Spektr Module </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Two crew members on the Russian
Mir space station today failed in their attempt to repair the
damage in the Spektr scientific module during a spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
Russian cosmonaut Anatoly Solovyov and NASA astronaut Michael
Foale were ordered by mission control to re-enter the Mir station
after they tried unsuccessfully to find a puncture in the module.
</P>
<P>
The damage was done on June 25 in a collision between a
Progress cargo craft and the orbital station, which forced a seal
off of the module from the main station.
</P>
<P>
The punctured module is now airless and one of its panels was
destroyed and the remaining three were disconnected by the crew
who fled it immediately.
</P>
<P>
Today's spacewalk started around 0100 GMT and the two
cosmonauts tried for more than five hours during the spacewalk to
locate the hole.
</P>
<P>
Several more spacewalks would be needed to find and repair the
puncture which depressurized the module, said Korolyov Mission
Control outside Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
