<HEADLINE> EU Requests U.S. to Change Satellite Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
warned the United States against violating world trade obligations
on satellite-based services.
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive body, the European Commission, requested the
U.S. side to change the rules issued on July 16 which would block
foreign operator's access to direct-to-home services and digital
satellite services in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The rules were said to have been adopted to implement the
commitments the United States made on satellite services made
under the Basic Telecoms Deal the World Trade Organization (WTO)
hammered out in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU member countries have been concerned about the
incompatibility of the rules with WTO, in particular with the
General Agreement on Trade in Services.
</P>
<P>
The EU warning followed a broad complaint last month about the
way the United States was implementing its general WTO
obligations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
