<HEADLINE> WTO Chief Confident of Italy's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy will certainly be a
founding member of the European Economic and Monetary Union and
the European single currency euro, chief of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Renato Ruggiero said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a symposium on international strategies on
management in Cernobbio, a resort town near Lake Como, Ruggiero
said, "We are in the homestretch both for the creation of the euro
on time and for Italy's participation."
</P>
<P>
Italy is likely to continue to draw benefit from its ongoing
economic recovery, he added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) has planned to launch the euro by
January 1, 1999. But scepticism is growing over whether the
deadline can be met as few members have been able to meet the
criteria set by the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
An EU meeting in April and May 1998 will decide which countries
among the 15 EU members will qualify for the single currency at
its launch in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero said that he was optimistic about the economic
prospect in Italy and throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that he did not pay much attention to recent
turbulence on the international financial markets. "Capital comes
and goes, as is natural after having made so many economies grow,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
