<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India Plunges Into Mourning for Mother Teresa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- News of the death of Mother
Teresa, widely hailed as the embodiment of love and compassion,
have plunged India into sorrow and grief.
</P>
<P>
The Mother, 87, breathed her last after a heart attack at 9:30
p.m. (local time) on Friday in Calcutta, capital of West Bengal
state.
</P>
<P>
President Kocheril Raman Narayanan and Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral led the nation in mourning the death of one who for
long years had come to be regarded as a legend in her lifetime.
</P>
<P>
Described the Mother as "an angel of mercy," Narayanan said
"such a one as her but rarely walks upon the earth."
</P>
<P>
Mother Teresa, he said, had spread love and compassion
throughout the world and brought succor and relief to the sick,
the needy and the poorest of the poor.
</P>
<P>
"Though she was a world citizen, she was particularly Indian in
the true spirit of our culture and her passing away is an immense
loss to millions of our people," the president noted.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Gujral, in his condolence message, said that
"Words fail me to express my sorrow. An apostle of peace and love,
Mother Teresa is no more with us."
</P>
<P>
The world, especially India, is poorer with her passing, the
prime minister said. "Hers was a life devoted to bringing love,
peace and joy to the people whom the world generally shuns," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Congress party President Sitaram Kesri, in his message,
described Mother Teresa as a symbol of the suffering humanity.
</P>
<P>
She was the mother of all poor children and handicapped, he
said, adding that her death was an irreparable loss for the whole
of mankind.
</P>
<P>
Pramod Mahajan, general secretary of the opposition Bharatiya
Janata Party, said Mother Teresa personified love and compassion
in its most sublime form and her work would be remembered by
generations to come.
</P>
<P>
West Bengal chief Minister Jyoti Basu also expressed deep grief
at the death of Mother Teresa, saying that his government had
given her all help in her work for the suffering humanity,
particularly for the children, orphans, disabled persons and
persons with incurable diseases.
</P>
<P>
Mother Teresa, whose real name was Agnes Gonxha Bojaxhiu, was
born in Skopje (now part of Macedonia), former Yugoslavia, on
August 27, 1910.
</P>
<P>
The daughter of an Albanian grocer, she was baptized at the age
of 18 and later sailed for India.
</P>
<P>
She made Calcutta her home where she set up the Missionaries of
Charity in late 1940s. The order now has more than 160 centers in
India which include schools, charitable dispensaries, homes for
lepers, orphans and the destitute.
</P>
<P>
She was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
