<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Won Likely to Continue Its Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean currency won is
likely to continue to drop in value against the U.S. dollar this
month before stabilizing in mid-October, Korea Institute of
Finance (KIF) forecast today.
</P>
<P>
The KIF predicted that the won-dollar exchange rate will remain
stable from mid-October to the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
It said that the won may come under strong pressure this month,
mainly because of growing concerns over turmoil in the local
financial market and a slowdown in overseas borrowing by domestic
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
It also cited the ongoing depreciation of Southeast Asian
currencies and the weak Japanese yen as reasons for the won's
possible drop.
</P>
<P>
But the institute forecast that the supply of U.S. dollars
would greatly expand by around mid-October thanks to the package
the government announced on August 25 to stablize financial market.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea is also expected to actively intervene in the
Seoul foreign-exchange market this month to help prop up the won.
</P>
<P>
The won has depreciated about 7 percent against the
U.S. currency in local trading so far this year. The South Korean
currency broke the key-psychological resistance level of 905 won
to the dollar Friday.
</P>
<P>
Though there is room for further appreciation of the won after
mid-October, the forecast said that the central bank would not
allow the won to rise against the U.S. dollar, as it fears a
further weakening of the international competitiveness of South
Korean businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
