<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Foreign Exchange Holdings Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign-exchange
holdings declined to 31.1 billion U.S. dollars last month from
33.6 billion dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea (BOK) attributed the drop, after a four-month
rise, mainly to the expansion in the central bank's supply of
foreign currency-denominated loans to domestic financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Most Korean financiers are facing serious difficulties in the
wake of the chain insolvencies and near-bankruptcies of large
conglomerates including Kia, Jinro and Hanbo.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts cited the BOK's disposal of enormous amounts of
foreign currency, in its bid to curb the surging won-dollar
exchange rate, as another factor behind the drop.
</P>
<P>
The basic won-dollar parity rate surged 13.60 won, or 1.5
percent, from 892 won per dollar at the end of July to 905.60 won
on September 5, as many financiers and private enterprises, who
feared a possible crisis in the domestic financial system, tried
to secure more foreign currencies, especially U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Market watchers are worried about a further drop of foreign
reserves because there are still unstable factors in the financial
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
