<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Dwellers Suffer from Acute Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Dwellers in Bangladesh's capital
of Dhaka are suffering from an acute shortage of water, sources in
the Water Supply and Sewerage Authorities (WSSA) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The water supply is about 40 percent short of the demand of the
ever growing population of the capital, they said.
</P>
<P>
The WSSA, an autonomous body responsible for operating the
sewerage system and supply of water in the metropolis, is now
supplying 860 million liters of water while the total requirement
is 1,350 million liters.
</P>
<P>
According to a United Nations report in June, Dhaka is among
the 50 largest cities in the world. Its population in 1996 stood
at nine million, making it the 22nd largest urban conglomeration.
</P>
<P>
Then UN report projected that Dhaka will continue to grow and,
by the year 2015, will have become the fifth largest city in the
world. At that time, its population will reach 19.5 million.
</P>
<P>
The WSSA has received hundreds of complaints from different
parts of the crowded city, the sources said, adding the whole city
is in the grip of water shortage.
</P>
<P>
The WSSA hardly could do anything with its limited resources
and networks to meet the increasing requirements of the millions,
a senior WSSA official said.
</P>
<P>
The water level has been going down by one meter every year due
to over extraction, the official said, adding that 98 percent of
the current water supply comes from ground water.
</P>
<P>
The existing system for procuring ground water has become
obsolete with the passage of time, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Now we are going to switch over to the surface water from the
ground water to overcome the crisis," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
