<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Inflation Declines: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The rate of inflation of Sri
Lanka is projected to be around 9.1 percent this year as against
the average inflation of 16 percent in the previous year,
according to the available indicators, Central Bank sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said this favorable development is due to improved
supply position of rice, vegetables, coconuts and subsidiary food
crops, lower increase in money supply and decline in interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Putting the index for August this year against that for
previous August, the indicated inflation is 7.1 percent, slightly
down from the 7.2 percent registered in the previous month, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
This is much lower than the inflation which stood as high as
16.8 percent at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The annual average inflation has been on a declining trend
since March this year when it reached a peak of 16.7 percent.
Furthermore, if the effect of administered price changes is
excluded, underlying inflation is estimated to be around 8.0
percent in August, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
