<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-Tenth Thailand's Plastics Factories Shut Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 percent of
Thailand's plastics factories have closed down in the last two
months, mainly because of a slump in sales to the vehicle and
electrical appliance industries.
</P>
<P>
At least 10,000 workers have been laid off as a result of the
closures since the Thai currency's float on July 2.
</P>
<P>
Because of the economic downturn, demand for plastics from the
automotive industry and sales to appliance makers have each
plunged 40 percent, the Bangkok Post today quotes Sanan
Ang-ubolkul, president of Srithai Superware Plc, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sanan said exports have not benefited from the plunge in the
value of the baht because producers have to pay in dollars for
imported raw materials used in making plastic. Factories have been
selling unused machinery and other assets to get cash.
</P>
<P>
Stocks of plastic goods would be released soon to help reduce
storage costs, Sanan said, adding that companies have put
expansion on hold and are trying to make more value-added
products.
</P>
<P>
The industry is squeezed for cash as it has lost a major credit
line when 58 debt-ridden and mismanaged finance companies were
suspended by the government, and buyers have also defaulted on
payment to the factories, citing financial problems.
</P>
<P>
Plastics suppliers are now accepting payment only in cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
