<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Yugoslavia Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in
Yugoslavia has rapidly increased since the United Nations Security
Council lifted sanctions on the country last October, said a
senior official here today.
</P>
<P>
Nebojsa Maljkovic, minister in charge of coordinating with
International Financial Institutions, said foreign partners
have shown great interest in Yugoslavia as prices and currency
are stable and industrial and agricultural production increases
steadly.
</P>
<P>
He noted that most of the foreign partners prefer to invest in
sectors such as electronic industry, oil industry, cement
industry, tobacco industry, shipbuilding industry, banking and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, External Trade Minister Borislav Vukovic noted that
Yugoslavia signed 1,757 agreements with foreign partners between
January in 1996 and June in 1997, absorbing 1.9 billion Deutsche
marks (about 1.05 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Germany and Italy lead the list with 222 and 211 agreements
respectively, followed by the United States and Russia, 49 and 18,
Vukovic said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
