<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Housing to Recover in 3 Years: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Thai
government's Land Department predicted that it will take at least
three years before supply and demand of housing can achieve
balance.
</P>
<P>
The housing market has been swamped by a huge oversupply of
stock, with many real estate consultants reporting that the market
has about 300,000 unoccupied units and 100,000-150,000 units
remain unsold.
</P>
<P>
This would be slowly absorbed by the market over the next two
to three years as the number of new projects was falling
significantly, said Vichien Rattanapirapong, director general of
the Land Department.
</P>
<P>
Developers are starting fewer projects this year because of the
housing oversupply and the central bank's lending squeeze.
</P>
<P>
Vichien said it is the worst crisis for the real estate
industry, adding that developers have painful experiences from the
property slump and oversupply.
</P>
<P>
Since the Gulf war, listed developers have acquired huge
amounts of land and have thus been burdened with high monthly
interest payments.
</P>
<P>
Despite the market oversupply, these developers will have to
develop at least part of their land, otherwise they would be
unable to repay loans to their creditors, Vichien said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
