<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Unchanged in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's jobless rate remained
unchanged at 9.0 percent in August from the previous month,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
In August, the country's employment rose by an estimated 55,000
for a six straight monthly increase. The growth far exceeded the
expectations of financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The markets expected an increase between 30,000 and 45,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The latest gain has brought to 277,000 the number of jobs
created so far this year, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, August growth in employment was accompanied by a similar
increase in the labor force, which left the number of people
looking for work little changed from July.
</P>
<P>
There were employment gains among both adults and youths in
August.
</P>
<P>
Employment among adults has been strengthening for several
months. Since February, gains total 127,000 for adult men and
112,000 for adult women.
</P>
<P>
For youths, the gains are more recent. August marked the third
consecutive month of growth with gains totaling 52,000 since May
-- the largest sustained increase since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Job growth in August was equally split between full- and
part-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
Since February, full-time employment has grown 1.7 percent,
while part-time gained 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the growth rate of part-time employment twice that of
full-time, the percentage of workers with part-time hours has
risen to 19.4 percent from 19.1 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
In August, employment in the private sector grew by an
estimated 87,000, while the public sector declined by 32,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
