<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother Teresa Passes Away in Calcutta, India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Nobel Laureate Mother Teresa
died of cardiac arrest in Calcutta, India, on Friday, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 87-year-old Teresa breathed her last at 9:30 p.m. (local
time) on Friday at her home at the headquarters of the
Missionaries of Charity in Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
She complained of chest pain, and several doctors were called
but she breathed her last a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
"The end was peaceful," a spokesperson for the Missionaries of
Charity said.
</P>
<P>
Baptized in 1929, the Albanian-born nun chose to make Calcutta
her home where she set up the Missionaries of Charity in 1947 to
serve the ailing members of the humanity.
</P>
<P>
She was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979 for what she had
done for the deprived and the destitute.
</P>
<P>
The Mother, who was twice hospitalized last year, was in ill
health for quite some time. She had a by-pass surgery and was also
on a permanent pace maker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Project for Domestic Use in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A large natural gas project in
Myanmar is under way to supply natural gas from Yadana offshore
field for domestic use, official paper the New Light of Myanmar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project is being implemented by TOTAL Oil Company of
France, UNOCAL Oil Company of the U.S. and Mitsui Company of Japan
in cooperation with the Myanmar Ministry of Energy to help boost
power generation and urea fertilizer production in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The project includes the laying of 238 kilometers of
50.8-centimeter gas pipeline from Yadana offshore field to Twantay
township of southern Yangon, the building of a fertilizer factory
which will produce 570,000 tons of urea annually and the building
of a 340-megawatt power station with a combined cycle power plant.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, another project for laying natural gas pipeline
running from the Yadana gas field in the Gulf of Mottma to
Thailand is also under way.
</P>
<P>
The Yadana natural gas field is jointly developed on a
production sharing basis by a foreign oil group, which comprises
TOTAL (France), UNOCAL (the United States) and PTTEP (Thailand),
and the state-run Myanmar Oil and Gas Enterprise (MOGE).
</P>
<P>
It is reported that profit from the project will be shared by
TOTAL with 31.24 percent, UNOCAL 28.26 percent, PTTEP 25.5 percent
and MOGE 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under a 30-year contract reached between the developers and the
 Petroleum Authority of Thailand (PAT) in January 1995, natural
gas from the Yadana field will be sold to Thailand starting July
1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
