<HEADLINE> Thai PM Supports Draft Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh Friday finally agreed to back the draft constitution,
easing a political tension that might disturb the six-party
coalition.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister vowed to seek amendments to the
draft later after the Parliament approves it.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit's announcement Friday that the coalition will
unanimously support the draft constitution came amid the mounting
pressure from the urban public, the military and within the
coalition, local newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit made this announcement in the wake of an urgent
meeting of coalition party leaders held about one hour later after
the Chart Pattana Party (CPP), the second largest coalition
partner, broke rank to announce it would back the draft
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit Thursday held consultations with leading Thai
businessmen, Army Chief Gen. Chettha Thananaro and Police Chief
Pracha Promnok, who urged the prime minister to support the draft
constitution to ease the political tension and prevent the
country's economy from plunging further.
</P>
<P>
CPP Secretary General Suwat Liptapallop said that the
government's decision to accept the new charter would ease
political pressure on the coalition from the public and the
government now has more breathing space to tackle the country's
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
However, some core members of the Constitution Drafting
Assembly insisted that the draft constitution would not be
amended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
