<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAEA Adopts Convention on Safety of Radioactive Fuel, Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A five-day conference of the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) ended here today with
the adoption of the Joint Convention on the Safety of Spent Fuel
Management and on the Safety of Radioactive Waste Management.
</P>
<P>
About 300 representatives from 84 countries and five
international organizations at the conference held hot debates
focusing on how to guarantee the safety of radioactive materials
being transported.
</P>
<P>
Many noted that they should at least be informed when the
materials are being transported through their territories.
</P>
<P>
But others, mostly Western nations, opted to continue the
current ruling that notification be given on a voluntary basis.
</P>
<P>
The final version of the convention received support from 62
countries in a show of hands, and is available for official
signing at the IAEA's 41st general conference which will begin
here on September 29.
</P>
<P>
The signatories will have to submit reports on how to implement
the convention in their countries.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA started to attach great importance to the management
of radioactive fuel and waste at its 38th general conference held
in 1994 when it decided to work out an international convention in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
A group comprising law and technology experts was set up by the
IAEA in March, 1995, to work the convention text with
environmental protection being a major theme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
