<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Condemns Jerusalem Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who is on a vacation here, strongly condemned
the terrorist attack in Jerusalem early Thursday, which killed at
least seven people and injured 192 others.
</P>
<P>
Albright told reporters Thursday that she felt deeply concerned
over the three bombings at the city's downtown shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official, who is expected to visit the Middle East
next week, also called on both Israel and Palestine to cooperate
and take effective measures to fight against terrorism and pave
way for restoration of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright had earlier issued a brief statement through the
American embassy here shortly after the bombings, saying that she
would "travel to the Middle East as scheduled."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday also ruled
out the possibility to postpone Albright's visit, saying that she
would go as originally scheduled despite the bombings.
</P>
<P>
He said the bombings added a new sense of urgency to Albright's
"travel to the Middle East as scheduled." 
</P>
