<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Adopts Market Mechanism in Traffic Infrastructures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province, home of the
late Chinese leader Mao Zedong, has introduced a market mechanism
for building traffic infrastructures including highways, railways
and water transport facilities.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, the provincial government has given up
the former practice of merely depending on state investment by
adopting a new, multi-formed investment method.
</P>
<P>
Stockholding and foreign funds have been used to develop the
infrastructures, on the principle of "those who invest could
benefit, and those who benefit should invest," according to local
officials in charge of transport.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the new policies have attracted a total of over 16
billion yuan of funds from the central and local governments as
well as from many domestic and overseas investors for building a
number of road, railway and port projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
