<HEADLINE> Ivankov Makes Golden Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Ivan Ivankov of Belarus, who
had torn an Achilles tendon before the Atlanta Olympics, took the
men's all-round title at the world gymnastics championships here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ivankov, who was injured in a training session in Atlanta and
missed the games, surged to lead the standing after the rings, the
fourth of six disciplines.
</P>
<P>
He was never behind since, scoring a final mark of 56.887 for
the victory of his first major competition after the injury.
</P>
<P>
Russian champion Alexei Bondarenko was a distant second,
collecting 56.061, while Japan's Naoya Tsukahara took the bronze
with 56.023.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Alexei Nemov, who won five Olympic medals in Atlanta,
had his hope dashed when he lost his hand grip during his rings
routine. He crashed to the mat.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Svetlana Khorkina of Russia won the women's all-round
title, beating Romania's Simona Amanar to second. Another Russian
Elena Produnova was third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
