<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-Ukrainian Summit Opens to Deepen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 5 (Xinhua) -- It is a strategic goal for
Ukraine to integrate with Europe and eventually gain the European
Union (EU) membership, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma said at
the first EU-Ukrainian summit here today.
</P>
<P>
The yearly summit is also attended by Jean-Claude Junker,
Luxembourg's prime minister who holds the present EU presidency,
and European Commission (EC) Chairman Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
Junker said Ukraine has to deepen its economic and political
reforms in order to join the organization, adding that EU would
continue to help the East European nation with its reforms.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is one of the largest recipients of EU aid among the
new independent states, Junker said, and EU has promised to offer
another 530 million ECU to Ukraine before 2000.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also spotlighted cooperation on developing
Ukraine's nuclear energy. Santer disclosed that the EC has decided
to donate 100 million ECU to repair the sarcophagus burying the
Chernobyl No. 4 reactor which exploded 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Santer added that the precondition for the grant is that
Ukraine guarantees nuclear safety by completely closing down the
Chernobyl plant by 2000 as agreed by the former Soviet republic and
the Group of Seven industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
The two parties agreed that the most important direction for EU
aid is to increase the capacities of the Rivne and Khmelynytsky
nuclear power plants, which are located in western Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
