<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon said it will lodge a complaint against
Israeli violation of truce with the five-nation ceasefire
committee regarding the heavy fighting in south Lebanon early on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese official National News Agency quoted Lebanese
Foreign Ministry officials as saying that the complaint will be
heard at a meeting of the committee expected to hold within 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Israeli soldiers were killed, four others wounded, and
one missing when Lebanese army and resistance fighters ambushed a
16-member Israeli commando who landed on the village of Nsariyyeh,
about 45 kilometers north of the Israeli border in attempt to
explode a Shiite Movement Amal base near the village, the news
agency reported. (Lebanon-Israel-Complaint)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The chief U.N. weapons inspector said Friday that
progress has been achieved in disarming Iraq of mass destruction
weapons with cooperation from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, chief of the United Nations Special Commission
on Iraq charged with removing the Iraqi mass-destruction weapons,
who arrived here Friday for a five-day visit, said the major
progress that was made in the area of removing rockets during the
past five weeks has led to significant results. (UN-Iraq-Progress)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Javier Solana, Secretary General of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), is to visit Sarajevo on the
eve of the September 13-14 Bosnian municipal election.
</P>
<P>
A NATO spokesman Friday disclosed the visit date and the
reinforcement of the NATO-led SFOR troops in Bosnia-Herzegovina,
from 31,000 to 39,000. Of the total, 3,000 will be stationed in
neighboring Croatia.
</P>
<P>
In another development, six F-16 jet fighters will fly from
NATO's Spandahlem base in Germany to Italy to join the 12 F-16s
already there for flights or aerial observation over Bosnia during
the coming election, the spokesman said. (NATO-Bosnian Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- President Jiang Zemin, meeting with Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on Friday, urged Japan to respect
China's stance on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Jiang reiterated the Chinese government stand that Taiwan is an
inalienable part of Chinese territory and that the Taiwan issue is
China's internal affair that no other country has the right to
interfere in.
</P>
<P>
He said the Japanese government has political obligations and
made a solemn promise on the issue of Taiwan in the China-Japan
Joint Statement and the China-Japan Treaty of Peace and
Friendship. (China-Japan-Jiang-Taiwan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government started imposition of
sanctions on Japanese shipping companies from Thursday which could
face 100,000 U.S. dollar fees each time they use a U.S. port,
according to U.S. press reports here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken in order to retaliate for what Washington
considers unfair restrictions on Japanese harbors.
</P>
<P>
However, spokesmen for the three Japanese companies, which had
ships expected to dock in U.S. ports on Friday, said there were no
plans to delay or reroute the ships. Meanwhile, they were hoping
for an agreement between the industry and Japan's Transport
Ministry that would satisfy Washington enough to delay or cancel
the sanctions. (US-Sanction-Japanese)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VILNIUS -- The international conference named Coexistence of
Nations and Good Neighborly Relations -- the Guarantee of Security
and Stability in Europe opened Friday in Lithuania's capital
Vilnius.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, initiated by Lithuanian President
Algirdas Brazauskas and his Polish counterpart, Alexander
Kwasniewski, was attended by the presidents of Belarus, Estonia,
Latvia, Ukraine, Bulgaria, Hungary, Finland, Moldavia and Romania
and Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that after the cold war, peace and development have
become a main trend of the world, where security and stability are
the key of the trend. All the countries of the world should make
every effort to create a peaceful and stable international
environment. (Europe-Security Conference)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Friday that cross-border military attack in southern Lebanon may
not be wrong despite the failure of such an attempt Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that it is too early
to draw a conclusion if Thursday's operation in which 12 Israeli
soldiers were killed went wrong, saying such attempts are always
heavily risky.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the comment after a meeting of inner security
cabinet. (Israel-South Lebanon-Clash) 
</P>
