<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Industrial Base Banks on Shareholding  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The shareholding system just
got a vote of confidence in China's Liaoning Province, the
country's largest industrial base, when the deputy general manager
of the Shanghai Stock Exchange, Wu Yalun, brought some good news
about the performance of Liaoning's listed companies.
</P>
<P>
"Of all the firms listed in Shanghai, the 38 from Liaoning were
among the best," Wu told Governor Wen Shizhen.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that the performance of these enterprises means hope
for state-owned enterprises that are having difficulties.
</P>
<P>
All large state-owned enterprises in Liaoning are to become
shareholding entities through joint-stock or incorporation and as
many of them as possible will be listed, except for some strategic
industries and some infrastructure industries.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is the leading industrial base of China, with 1,000
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises, or about a tenth
of the national total. This concentration made it a major economic
powerhouse during the years of the planned economy.
</P>
<P>
However, these state-owned enterprises, like those elsewhere,
have failed to adapt to market competition and have been mired in
financial difficulties since China began its market reforms in the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Vice Premier Zhu Rongji said during an inspection tour of
Liaoning that a greater effort must be made to get most of the
state-owned enterprises out of difficulties in three years, but he
said he is positive about the work Liaoning has done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Industrial Base Banks on Shareholding (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liaoning was one of the first provinces or municipalities to
try shareholding and has more than 200 joint-stock companies. It
has 38 listed firms. Nearly 80 percent of these have good economic
returns.
</P>
<P>
The shareholding system will help improve management and boost
productivity, the governor says. It provides new financial
resources needed for equipment renovation and technology imports.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 alone, Liaoning completed more than 140 technical
renovation projects with funds raised through shares. Since last
year, the listed companies have raised 6.67 billion yuan by
issuing shares.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Danshi, a company official, told Xinhua that "every day
dozens of our shareholders call in to inquire about the well-being
of our company and this makes me and all the workers feel obliged
to do our best to improve our business record."
</P>
<P>
"If we don't do a good job, we'll feel terrible for our
investors," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Sisheng, a division chief of the provincial planning
commission, said that the shareholding system is an appropriate
organizational form for state-owned enterprises in Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Lin Muxi, deputy director of the economic research institute of
Liaoning University, agreed and added that the system is a good
combination of public ownership and the market economy.
</P>
<P>
However, whether the system will produce the desired effects
depends on government's structural reforms, including its role in
policy-making, and reforms in the social security system and other
sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
