<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis, Williams Advance to U.S. Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Martina Hingis of
Switzerland and unseeded Venus Williams of the United States
advanced to the women's final of the 10.12 million U.S. dollars
U.S. Open tennis championships Friday after achieving victories in
semifinals at Flushing, New York.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Hingis moved into the position by beating sixth
seed Lindsay Davenport of the United States in straight sets, 6-2,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Williams fought off two match points in the
third set tiebreak and rallied for a 7-6 (7-5), 4-6, 7-6 (9-7)
victory over No. 11 Irina Spirlea of Romania.
</P>
<P>
In the first semifinals Friday, Hingis avenged a three-set loss
to Davenport in the semifinals of the Acura Classic in Manhattan
Beach, California, last month, one of her only two defeats in 64
matches this year.
</P>
<P>
She was successful moving Davenport from side to side to set up
easy winners and frustrated her repeatedly with drop shots.
</P>
<P>
Davenport got off to a strong start, breaking Hingis in the
opening game of the match. But after she hold for a 2-0 lead,
Hingis put her game in high gear and won the next six games to
take the set.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, each player was broken on her first two
service games. However, Hingis held for a 3-2 lead finally and
broke Davenport for the sixth consecutive.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon match, Williams, who needed two hours and 42
minutes to defeat Spirlea, is the first unseeded female player in
the open era to reach the U.S. Open final and the first
African-American woman to reach a Grand Slam final since Zina
Garrison at Wimbledon in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Spirlea built a 6-4 lead in the third-set tiebreak and appeared
ready to advance to her first Grand Slam final. However, Williams
connected on a spectacular backhand winner that barely caught the
sideline and Spirlea netted a forehand to tie it at 6-6. Williams
wasted a match point at 7-6, but Spirlea netted a backhand to set
up match point and then went wide with a backhand to give Williams
the dramatic victory.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia and Daniel Vacek of the
Czech Republic captured their second Grand Slam doubles title of
the year by defeating the Swedish team of Jonas Bjorkman and
Nicklas Kulti, 7-6 (10- 8), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
In women's doubles semifinals, Gigi Fernandez of the United
States and Natasha Zvereva of the Belarus defeated Nicole Arendt
of the United States and Manon Bollegraf of the Netherlands, 3-6,
7-6 (7-4), 6-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
