<HEADLINE> Greek Prime Minister on Athens' Balkan Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Costas Simitis
said tonight Athens' Balkan policy and a stronger Greek economy
through joining European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) were
basic conditions for turning northern Greece into a development
center for the Balkan Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural address to this year's International Trade
Fair in the northern Greek port city of Thessaloniki, Simitis said
that another condition for uplifting northern Greece into its
central Balkan role was the promotion of infrastructure networks
in transport, communications, energy, and technology, as well as
stock market and banking facilities.
</P>
<P>
He stressed Greece's contribution to the promotion of peace,
security and cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The success of our policy in the Balkans depends on
strengthening our economy, its competitiveless, its ability to
participate in time in the third phase of the EMU," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a condition for Greece's far-reaching Balkan plan, Simitis
laid emphasis on measures designed to strengthen Greece's social
fabric, such as administrative devolution and cohesion,
educational reform, health care and welfare. He stressed at the
same time the need for security in the border regions against the
adverse effects of illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
As for the prospects of Greece's economy in 1998, he said that
1998 would be a difficult year, the year of the big push forward,
in which the steps already made would have to be completed,
entering a "dynamic orbit." 
</P>
