<HEADLINE> New York Commercial Bank to Acquire First Bank of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Commercial Bank of New York
(Commercial Bank) announced today it has signed an agreement by
which it will acquire all of the stock of First Bank of the
Americas (First Bank), which will thereafter be merged into
Commercial Bank.
</P>
<P>
The purchase price, as currently calculated, is approximately
48 million U.S. dollars, according to a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
The transaction is subject to various regulatory and
shareholder approvals and is expected to close before December 31,
1997, it said.
</P>
<P>
As of June 30, 1997, First Bank had total assets of
approximately 400 million U.S. dollars, total deposits of about
365 million U.S. dollars and shareholders' equity of about 33
million U.S. dollars. It has been operating with losses in its
recent past, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The purchase price is approximately 1.5 times First Bank's June
30, 1997 book value.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the agreement, Jacob Berman, president of
Commercial Bank, said, "We will add to our existing franchise
eight branch locations with approximately 365 million U.S. dollars
of additional deposits and assets."
</P>
<P>
This acquisition represents considerable opportunities for
additional revenue generation and cost savings. With this
transaction, Commercial Bank will reach the next plateau on its
path towards controlled growth.
</P>
<P>
As of June 30, 1997, Commercial Bank of New York had total
assets of 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, total deposits of 830 million
U.S. dollars and shareholders' equity of 81 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commercial Bank's business concentrates on small and medium-sized
businesses, private banking services to international and domestic
clients, and retail banking services through its branch network in
the New York metropolitan area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
