<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Chip Sales Rise in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Global semiconductor sales
surpassed 11.61 billion U.S. dollars in July, a 13.3 percent
increase over the same period in 1996, according to the
Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA).
</P>
<P>
July's sales -- 1.367 billion dollars higher than July 1996 --
continue a growth trend beginning from May, when 1997 sales
exceeded May 1996 sales by 167 million dollars. Sales for June
1997 surpassed June 1996 sales by 807 million dollars, the
California-based SIA said in its monthly Global Sales Report
issued today.
</P>
<P>
The most dramatic year-to-year change occurred in the Americas
market, which experienced a 19.4 percent increase to 3.845 billion
dollars in sales for July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sales in the Asia-Pacific market hit 2.531 billion dollars in
July 1997, a 16.1 percent increase over sales in July 1996. On a
year-to-year basis, sales also jumped in Europe, increasing by
12.4 percent to 2.297 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
On a month-to-month comparison, global chip sales rose 1.8
percent in July 1997, a 202 million dollar increase over June
1997. The largest increase surfaced in Japan, where sales grew 6.4
percent from 2.761 billion dollars in June 1997 to 2.937 billion
dollars in July 1997. Sales in the Americas market at 3.845
billion dollars represent a 0.2 percent increase over June 1997
sales.
</P>
<P>
The report said the numbers in this report are a three-month
rolling average of actual sales in the world's major chip markets.
</P>
<P>
Data for the Global Sales Report was compiled by the World
Semiconductor Trade Statistics, an organization of 70 chip
companies worldwide, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
