<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Ambassador Asks Israel to Pull Out of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese ambassador to
Washington today required Israel to pull its forces out of
southern Lebanon a day after an Israeli commando raid ended in
failure with nine Israelis killed by guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
"It's time for Israel to re-think its presence in southern
Lebanon and pull out its forces," Mohammed Shatah told reporters
after he called at the U.S. State Department.
</P>
<P>
Israeli chief of staff Amnon Shakak said an Israeli commando
force which landed on the Lebanese coast north of Tyre was blown
up when explosives they were carrying were detonated during an
ambush by guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Shatah said the incident showed the situation in
southern Lebanon could not be resolved by an Israeli presence
there. Israel maintains a so-called security zone in southern
Lebanon designed to protect its frontier from guerrilla attack.
</P>
<P>
Shatah reaffirmed his government's policy that if Israel
withdrew from southern Lebanon, the Lebanese army would assume
control there, which would end the reasons for the violence in the
area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State Department spokesman James Foley called for
maximum restraint by all parties after the explosion incident in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very delicate moment in the Middle East, throughout
the Middle East, including in Lebanon, and we urge all the parties
to exercise maximum restraint," he said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to see an escalation of the cycle of
violence. So we need a defusing of tensions in southern Lebanon,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will travel to the Middle
East next week, visiting Israel, the Palestinian Authority, Egypt,
Jordan, Syria and Saudi Arabia, in an attempt to revive the peace
process that has been suspended since early March.
</P>
<P>
A visit to Lebanon has not yet been decided, but the issue will
certainly come up when Albright holds talks with leaders of Israel
and Syria during her first trip to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
