<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM Pays Tribute to Mother Teresa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair paid tribute to Mother Teresa, who died of a heart attack in
India early today, saying "her spirit will live on as an
inspiration to all of us."
</P>
<P>
Blair, whose country is soaked in deep mourning of the violence
death of Princess Diana, said in a statemment, "In a week already
filled with tragedy, the world will be saddened that one of its
most compassionate servants has died."
</P>
<P>
"Mother Teresa devoted her life to the poor and her spirit will
live on as an inspiration to all of us," Blair said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Buckingham Palace described Mother Teresa as an
"renowned international figure," saying her untimely death was "an
extremely sad coincidence" for Britain, which is preparing a
national funeral for Princess Diana who died in a Paris car crash
last week.
</P>
<P>
Mother Teresa, known as "Saint of the Gutters" for her work
with the poor, won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979 for bringing hope
and dignity to millions of poor people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
