<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Impatient Over Long-Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations was getting impatient that the U.N. human
rights group in the Democratic Republic of the Congo had not been
allowed to start its long-delayed work to investigate the alleged
massacre of Rwandan Hutus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, Council president Bill Richardson
of the United States said, "My sense is that patience is running
out and the Council will deal with this issue once and for all on
Monday."
</P>
<P>
"It is critically important that the U.N. human rights
investigation mission have full, unimpeded access immediately," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Local human rights groups and aid officials believe that
thousands of Rwandan Hutus were massacred this year by Kabila's
troops and their Rwandan Tutsi backers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
