<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Airlines to Reduce Aircraft Noise Emission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- United Airlines of the United
States announced today that it will embark on a program to reduce
noise emissions from its fleet by replacing a considerable number
of its aircraft.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, it will have reduced aircraft noise
emissions by 25 percent more than Federal standards, it said in
a press release from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total 579 aircraft in its stock, 48 will be retired
by the end of 1998, and another 57 will be taken in by the end of
1998, it said, adding noise-reducing hush kits will be installed
on the engines of 99 Boeing aircraft by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The new fleet will be comprised of Boeing 747, 757, 767, and
777 aircraft as well as Airbus A320 and 319 aircraft, it said.
</P>
<P>
As Chicago's hometown airline and the largest air carrier in
the world, United Airlines offers nearly 2,300 flights a day to
136 destinations in 30 countries, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
