<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Inspector: Progress in Disarming Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The chief U.N. weapons
inspector said today that progress has been achieved in disarming
Iraq of mass destruction weapons with cooperation from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, chief of the United Nations Special Commission
on Iraq (UNSCOM) charged with removing the Iraqi mass-destruction
weapons, arrived here today for a five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters upon his arrival, he said the major
progress that was made in the area of removing rockets during the
past five weeks has led to significant results.
</P>
<P>
Butler expressed relief over the intensive efforts exerted by
the two sides to meet the agenda that was agreed upon during his
previous and first visit to Iraq as UNSCOM chief five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
He said he has a good impression about the intensive work of
the Iraqi government since his previous visit.
</P>
<P>
Butler replaced Rolf Ecues as executive chairman of the UNSCOM
on July 1. Ecues had complained of non-cooperation from Iraq,
while Baghdad rejected the charge.
</P>
<P>
A UNSCOM report to be tabled to the U.N. Security Council on
October 11 will be objective and in the interests of the Iraqi
people if Iraq complies with the previously concluded agreements,
Butler said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-imposed sanctions on Iraq since 1990 will not be
lifted before the UNSCOM verifies that Iraq has destroyed all its
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Butler pointed out that the report be compiled only after his
second round of talks with the Iraqi side under Deputy Prime
Minister Tareq Aziz on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
Butler went on to say that he would inquire of the Iraqi side
whether it used any of the banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the mission of the monitoring and
inspection officials is to find out the truth.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors' team of the U.N. special Commission on Iraq
(UNSCOM), comprising some 150 experts, is to make sure that Iraq
is no longer possessing chemical and biological weapons or capable
of producing long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
During his previous visit to Iraq, Butler reached an agreement
with the Iraqi authorities on the working plan for the removal of
the Iraqi ballistic, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
At least five UN inspection teams have come to Baghdad since
last July.
</P>
<P>
Iraq hopes that Butler's visit will yield a recommendation for
lifting the U.N.-imposed sanctions or easing the embargo on Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
