<HEADLINE> Bogus Elector's Cards Exposed in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today said that 5,000 elector's cards had been fraudulently
printed and distributed in Baringo Central Constituency in a bid
to undermine the forthcoming general elections.
</P>
<P>
At a rare press conference held here, the president noted that
thousands of counterfeit elector's cards are suspected to be
circulating around the country with the purpose to have the
elections dismissed as a sham.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that his government will not condone any "monkey
business" ahead of the elections and emphasized that he is
personally committed to ensuring free and fair elections later
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan head of state displayed to the media one of the
bogus cards which is an exact replica of the voter's card issued
by the Kenya Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is not afraid nor threatened by any challenger
from his constituency of Baringo Central during the coming
general elections, but cautioned that he will not tolerate
deceptive methods by those hoping to oppose him.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kenya Electoral Commission and the National
Registration have unearthed more than 1.000 cases of
double-registration.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission Chairman Justice Chesoni assured
Kenyans that the commission had in place a double check, the fool
proof system to counter election fraud.
</P>
<P>
He warned that all those who had double registered in a bid
to cheat would relentlessly be pursued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
