<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Believes Russian Missiles Delivery on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government
believes that surface-to-air missiles S-300 contracted to be
bought from Russia will be deployed in Cyprus on schedule despite
Turkish threats and acts, a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is searching recently commercial ships passing through
the Bosporus Strait and suspected of carrying missile components
in an effort to prevent S-300's deployment in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides told his daily press
briefing that the contract signed with Russian manufacturers
"secures safe transport and deployment of the S-300 missiles" on
the island, expected in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that these surface-to-air missiles are part of
the government's necessary measures to bolster its defense.
</P>
<P>
The missile deal, which was reached in January, has enraged
Turkey and Turkish Cypriots and Ankara has threatened to launch
military strikes against Cyprus if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has repeatedly said that the deal could
be canceled if Turkey and Turkish Cypriots agree to Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides' proposal for demilitarization of the
island, or if there is substantial progress on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting recent Turkish inspections of ships sailing through
the Bosporus Straits from the Black Sea to the Aegean,
Christofides said the Cypriot government believes that
international treaties should be respected and observed.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said Cyprus will investigate the press
reports that the secret services of the U.S., Israel and
Azerbaijan are providing Turkey with information of the S-300
possible transport to Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
