<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air France Head Resigns in Quarrel with Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Christian Blanc, the president
of the French national carrier Air France, announced today that he
will quit his job because of his dispute with the government over
the privatization of the air company.
</P>
<P>
This brought to an end a week-long quarrel between him and
Lionel Jopin's Socialist government and Communist Transport
Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot. Blanc strongly advocates the
privatization but it is stiffly opposed by Jospin and Gayssot,
whose parties promised during the last legislative campaign to
stop the privatization process launched by the former rightwing
government of Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
In a statement announcing his withdrawal from the presidency of
Air France, Blanc, who was nominated to the post by the former
rightwing government of Edouard Balladur, said that privatization
"is the only way" to ensure the development of Air France.
</P>
<P>
He said the state must sell more than 50 percent of the
stocks of Air France, a demand rejected by Jospin who insists that
the state must maintain a majority of the stocks to keep the
company ``the last great Western transport enterprise with a
public majority of stocks.''
</P>
<P>
Blanc insisted that privatization of Air France would bring
about solid alliance with other international air companies which
buy its stocks, to make the air company one of the best in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The French presidential office today expressed regret over the
resignation of Blanc, and again called for an adaptation of the
French economy to the changing world economic situation.
</P>
<P>
``It remains a key stake for France which should pursue in this
field the indispensable efforts of modernization and adaptation of
the company,'' said the Elysee Palace in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Dominique Strauss-Kahn said today that the
state will open part of the stocks of Air France to the market,
but stressed that ``privatization is not on the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
In an article published in the Communist daily l"Humanite'' on
Tuesday, Gayssot presented the formula of ``neither privatization,
nor status quo'' for innovating Air France.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission adopted a French plan in 1994 to
privatize Air France at a value of 20 billion francs (4 billion
U.S. dollars), on the condition that the French government
participate in the privatization process.
</P>
<P>
``We don't demand that a enterprise should be private or
public, but that it should be competitive and that it follow the
rules of the market,'' said the commission today in reaction to
the resignation of Blanc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
