<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Safeguards Necessity of Cross-border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said today that cross-border military attack in
southern Lebanon may not be wrong despite the failure of such an
attempt last night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that it is too early
to draw a conclusion if Thursday's operation in which 12 Israeli
soldiers were killed went wrong, saying such attempts are always
heavily risky.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the comment after a meeting of inner security
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The 12 Israeli navy commandos were killed last night in
fighting with Lebanese troops and guerrillas as they were making
their way to a target in an operation beyond the
1,000-square-kilometer "security zone".
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army spokesman said Lebanon is responsible for the
return of the bodies. Four other commandos were hurt in the fight
and one of them seriously.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the "security zone" in South Lebanon in 1985 to
prevent cross border attacks by anti-Israeli
guerrillas. Hezbollah, a Muslim Shiite movement backed by Iran,
has been battling to force Israel out of this buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman said, during his visit to the
wounded navy commandos in a hospital, that Israel must negotiate
with Syria if it wants to insure calm on the northern border and
the only way to end the conflict in south Lebanon is through such
dialog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
