<DOCNO> XIE19970906.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG to Strictly Enforce Embargo on S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG) today announced it will take military actions to
enforce embargo on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG press statement warned all ships and aircraft to
keep off Sierra Leone's territorial waters and airspace as it is
enforcing the embargo approved by the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
The force is to "take any necessary measures against any ship,
vehicle or aircraft violating the ECOWAS decisions", it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the force reportedly fired shells
on two container ships which were trying to berth in Freetown to
unload rice and other foodstuffs on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The junta, which seized power in the May 25 coup, has accused
ECOMOG of killing some 50 civilians and seriously wounding nearly
20 others during the discriminate bombardment.
</P>
<P>
In an immediate reaction Thursday, ECOMOG Commander
Major-General Victor Malu denied the accusation, saying that the
force was enforcing the embargo ordered by ECOWAS last week.
</P>
<P>
"This final warning has become necessary in view of the
continuous attempt by some unscrupulous shippers to violate the
ECOWAS embargo in total disregard for the Heads of State and
Government of the sub-region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It warned, "Any ship seen violating the ECOWAS economic
embargo shall be doing so at their risk as they will be attacked
by the ECOMOG forces."
</P>
<P>
However, vessels bringing goods meant for humanitarian
purposes will be exempted after they have been duly inspected by
ECOMOG forces, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The embargo, according to last week's ECOWAS summit in Abuja,
Nigeria, is part of the sub-regional effort "to restore the
democratically elected government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
to power as soon as possible".
</P>
<P>
Items covered by the "general and total embargo" are all
supplies of petroleum products, arms and military vehicles and
equipment to Sierra Leone, including police equipment and related
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, ECOWAS leaders ordered that member states shall
prohibit any and all traffic from entering the territory or
territorial waters of Sierra Leone, carrying such goods.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS members are also required to prohibit all members of
the "illegal regime", military officers, as well as members of
their families, and other persons directly or indirectly
connected with the regime, from entering their respective
territories.
</P>
<P>
While sale or supply of the listed goods to Sierra Leone is
banned, member states have to prevent any activities by their
nationals or on their territories which would promote the export
or transshipment of commodities or products originating in
Sierra Leone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
