<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iraq Sign Contracts Under Oil-for-Food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Holding Company for
Food Industries today signed three contracts worth 17 million
U.S. dollars with Iraq for the supply of household materials.
</P>
<P>
Under the contracts, which are the first between the two sides
under the second phase of the oil-for-food deal, Egypt will export
to Iraq 23,000 tonnes of shortening, soap and detergents.
</P>
<P>
Signatories to the contracts were Chairman of the Egyptian
company Abdusattar Nasseb and Chairman of the Iraqi Public Company
for Food Trade Yousef el-Anni.
</P>
<P>
The contracts would be effective soon after their approval by
the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the first phase of the Iraqi-U.N. deal, the Egyptian
company had been contracted to export to Iraq shortening, sugar,
soap and detergents worth 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council agreed early June to extend the
agreement allowing Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars in oil for
another six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies.
</P>
<P>
The deal is an exemption from the U.N. sanctions imposed after
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. U.N. diplomats have said they will
not consider lifting the sanctions until they are satisfied that
Iraq has fully cooperated with UN arms inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
