<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-05 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Pro-Kurdish Activists Expelled by Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Istanbul police today
deported three pro-Kurdish foreigners, saying their activities
constituted a violation of Turkey's law.
</P>
<P>
An Italian diplomat in Ankara was among the three deportees,
who were taken into custody Thursday along with other 18
pro-Kurdish activists, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
These activists were detained by police when they tried to
hold a press conference in defiance of a warning.
</P>
<P>
Two diplomats from Italy and Britain were freed soon after
detention. The remaining foreign detainees will not be deported
until Sunday, police said.
</P>
<P>
A group of foreigners, mostly Europeans, arrived in Turkey
recently under a "Peace Train" plan to rally support for the
Kurds living in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government had tried to abort the plan, but some
activists managed their way into the country.
</P>
<P>
The Kurdish issue is a long-standing problem annoying the
Turkish government. The outlawed Kurdish Worker's Party (PKK) has
been fighting a 13-year guerrilla war against the Turkish
government in an attempt to establish an independent Kurdish
state in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
