<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Called to Build Self-reliance Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today called on the
country's public and private sectors to make joint efforts in the
building of a self-reliance economy.
</P>
<P>
Various progressive policies are being implemented under the
philosophy of guided deregulation and fiscal discipline so as to
build a solid economy, said Oladipo Diya, Chief of General Staff.
</P>
<P>
"The federal government is optimistic about the future of our
great nation," added Diya, who is also Vice-Chairman of the
Provisional Ruling Council, Nigeria's highest policy-making body.
</P>
<P>
Diya was speaking at the 10-day 1997 Lagos State Annual Trade
Fair which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The trade fair, tagged as "EKO EXPO '97", is held under the
theme of Lagos State at 30 -- Economic Growth and Development
through Public and Private Sectors' Initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of local companies and those from several other
neighboring states are at the fair promoting their products
manufactured with domestic resources, as well as services
available in the state.
</P>
<P>
Lagos State Military Administrator, Mohamed Marwa, said his
state had adopted a number liberalized policies to encourage the
development of medium-sized and small enterprises, tourism and
other sectors.
</P>
<P>
He urged domestic and foreign investors to come to the state
to embrace business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The one-time national capital, Lagos State was set up in May
1967 and has been developed into the financial and economic nurve
center of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, some 60-70 percent of commerical
transactions in Nigeria is confirmed or finalized in Lagos, which
accounts for over 60 percent of the total value of industrial
investments in the six major industrial centers of Nigeria and
over half of the country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated population of 10 million, Lagos also boasts
the largest seaport in west Africa, making it a sub-regional
shipping center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
