<HEADLINE> Disgraced Arizona Governor Leaving Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Governor Fife Symington of
Arizona of the United States, convicted earlier this week on
federal fraud charges, was to leave office officially at 5 p.m.
today.
</P>
<P>
But he made his final exit from his office late Thursday, aides
said. He planned to leave on vacation this afternoon, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Jane Hull will be acting governor until she
is formally sworn in Monday. Arizona does not have a lieutenant
governor.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the day after he was convicted of seven fraud
counts that could land him in prison, he met with Hull.
</P>
<P>
Hull is the second Arizona secretary of state in a decade to
take over for a fallen governor. Governor Evan Mecham was
impeached and removed from office in 1988 and later acquitted in a
criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
Defense attorney John Dowd said Thursday he would file papers
next month asking U.S. District Judge Roger Strand to set aside
Symington's conviction on seven felony counts of bank and wire
fraud.
</P>
<P>
Symington's sentencing is scheduled for November 10. 
</P>
