<HEADLINE> Hurricane Moving Towards Northeast Caribbean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane warnings were
posted today for the Leeward Islands of the northeast Caribbean as
tropical storm Erika became a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
Warning flags could be seen on Antigua, Montserrat, Barbuda,
Nevis, St. Kitts, Anguilla, St. Barthelemy and Dutch and French
St. Martin. Puerto Rico and the U.S. and British Virgin Islands
were under a hurricane watch, an Associated Press report from
Puerto Rico said.
</P>
<P>
At 11 a.m. EDT, Erika was about 250 miles (420 km) east of
Antigua, moving west-northwest at about 13 mph (22 km). Its motion
was expected to continue through Saturday morning. Its center was
toward the northeastern Leeward Islands.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami said that hurricane
force winds extended up to 105 miles (176 km) northeast of the
center. Rainfall of 5 to 10 inches was possible.
</P>
<P>
In July, Hurricane Danny caused severe flooding and scattered
damage along the coast of Louisiana and Alabama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
