<HEADLINE> US Imposes Sanctions Against Japanese Shippers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
started imposition of sanctions on Japanese shipping companies
from Thursday which could face 100,000 U.S. dollar fees each time
they use a U.S. port, according to U.S. press reports here today.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken in order to retaliate for what Washington
considers unfair restrictions on Japanese harbors.
</P>
<P>
The first three ships facing fines were expected to dock in
U.S. ports today. Kawasaki Kisen Kaisha Ltd., Mitsui O.S.K. Lines
Ltd. and Nippon Yusen KK had full container ships headed for
Seattle, Houston and Tacoma, Washington state.
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen for the three companies said there were no plans to
delay or reroute the ships. Meanwhile, they were hoping for an
agreement between the industry and Japan's Transport Ministry that
would satisfy Washington enough to delay or cancel the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were proposed in February by the independent U.S.
Federal Maritime Commission to retaliate for alleged restrictive
practices against U.S. shippers in Japanese harbors.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were to take effect on April 14, but President
Clinton suspended them until September 4, hoping Japan's Transport
Ministry could do something to end the alleged restrictions.
</P>
<P>
These include a practice known as "prior consultation," in
which any changes in shipping practices must first be discussed
with the Japan Harbor Transportation Association. The U.S.
commission also accuses Japanese harbors of discriminating against
U.S. carriers that attempt to run their own operations in Japanese
ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
