<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Africans Receive Olympic Bid Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The news that Cape Town
will not host the 2004 Olympic Games is not all doom and gloom
and South Africa will continue to bid, political and business
leaders said this evening.
</P>
<P>
In Lausanne, Switzerland, the International Olympic Committee
today named Athens the bid winner of the 2004 Olympic Games,
beating the other four bidders, namely Cape Town, Stockholm,
Buenos Aires and Rome.
</P>
<P>
The decision "should encourage all of us to redouble our
efforts for the 2008 bid," the ruling African National Congress
(ANC) said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"In this way we can affirm in no uncertain terms our
determination to ensure that Africa takes its rightful place
among the continents of the world and that, by 2008, the
continent is firmly established on the path to reconstruction and
renewal," the statement continued.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Acting President Mangosuthu Buthelezi said his
people should be proud of the fact that Cape Town had qualified
for the last round of the bid.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela and his deputy Thabo
Mbeki are now staying in Lausanne along with Cape Town's bidding
delegation.
</P>
<P>
"Qualifiying to the last round was itself an achievement,"
Buthelezi told a hushed crowd at Cape Town's grand parade after
Athens was chosen as the successful bidder.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi told about 60,000 people that the whole Africa, from
Egypt to South Africa, is very disappointed, adding however, "We
don't let the disappointment put us down".
</P>
<P>
"We have our own pride and Africa's efforts to bid the Olympic
Games have just started," the acting president announced.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town Mayor William Bantom assured that the city had won
the attention of the world, and Tourism and foreign investment will
continue to gain in momentum in the future.
</P>
<P>
No one can deny that Cape Town and indeed South Africa as a
whole is now firmly placed on the international stage, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Uys, Executive Officer of Cape Town's city authorities,
noted, "As we worked together in a new spirit of cooperation
and partnership to win the Olympics, let us jointly strive to
face the challenges of the next century, for the betterment of
all our peoples."  
</P>
</TEXT>
