<HEADLINE> Zambia Bans Import of Wheat Flour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official
declared here today that the Zambian government has banned with
immediate effect the importation of wheat flour into the country
to promote local wheat milling, Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ackim Nkole, deputy minister of commerce, trade and industry,
said that Zambia was capable of meeting the nation's annual
demand of 120,000 tons of floor from the locally produced wheat.
</P>
<P>
However, wheat instead of the flour could still be imported
because the government wanted to increase capacity for local
value added production of wheat flour which has been eroded by
the import of flour, Nkole explained.
</P>
<P>
He said that most of the wheat milling industries are being
restructured in accordance with the new economic environment and
the government was taking measures to increase the economic scale
of local millers.
</P>
<P>
The official added that the ministry would work hand in hand
with the Zambian revenue authority to monitor items in transit at
entry points on the borders.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the ban would also help curb smuggling of the same
commodity which has become pampant of late.
</P>
<P>
Nkole assured the public that the ban couldn't lead to
shortage of flour since the government has done its "homework".
</P>
<P>
Although Zambia has leberalised its economy, the government
has a duty to put certain measures in place to ensure that the
"playing ground" is even, said the deputy minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
