<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Appeals to Refugees to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic
of Congo has called on its refugees hosted in Tanzania to return
home and join fellow citizens in re-building the nation.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Congolese Foreign Minister Bizima
Karaha who has come here to attend the Great Lakes Region summit
on Burundi that just concluded here.
</P>
<P>
Karaha told local press that it is imparative that good
citizens of Congo (former Zaire) who fled their country for some
reasons should go home.
</P>
<P>
"We have made arrangements between the government of Congo,
Tanzania and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) for the refugees to be repatriated home on voluntary
basis," the Congolese foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "I understand that some 600 or so out of the 74,000
have been repatriated after consultations between the relevant
parties -- the government of Congo, Tanzania and the UNHCR."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We do not want antagonism. The country can only be
run by Congolese and not anybody else. So for those who fear that
the government will take them to task after returning home should
be rest assured that they will be safe."
</P>
<P>
As for some of the refugees who fled the country because of
their ill doings, Karaha said, "They can come back home as good
citizens, declare what they have possibly stolen if they may so
wish."
</P>
<P>
The Congolese refugees left their homeland in the last few
years to flee the civil strifes in their country. 
</P>
