<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, Give Up Early Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all gave up their early gains and ended off their best levels
today, undermined by Wall Street's retreat.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London had gained 37 points on the FTSE 100
index earlier in the day, inspired by US jobs data which were
originally regarded as good for financial markets, before ending
only 2.9 points up at 4,994.2, failing to recapture the key
5,000-point level this week, but 176.7 points higher on last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that US payroll data initially eased fears of a
rate rise but analysts later said the figures gave mixed signals
as the August data was dampened by half a month's United Parcel
Service strike.
</P>
<P>
German shares closed higher despite a session spent trading in
narrow ranges. Traders said volumes were thin with market players
reluctant to adopt new position ahead of US non-farm payrolls
figures. The DAX-30 index ended at 4,100.67, up 28.99 points or
0.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
Stocks on the Paris bourse retreated in line with bonds, with
the CAC-40 index down 2.48 points at 2,924.51 by the close of the
session, but 154.02 points higher on last week. 
</P>
