<HEADLINE> Palestinians Stick to Zero Tolerance Toward Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A visiting Palestinian
delegation said today that the Palestinian Authority would stick
to the policy of "zero tolerance" towards terrorism after a triple
suicide bombing Thursday killed seven people and injured more than
150 at a West Jerusalem shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of President (Yasser) Arafat and the Palestinian
Authority remains and will continue to be a policy of zero
tolerance to terror and violence whether committed by Israelis or
Palestinians against Palestinians and Israelis," top negotiator
Saeb Erekat told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after his talks with U.S. mediator Dennis
Ross earlier today at the State Department. The talks, which
followed the ones Wednesday between the U.S. and Israeli
officials, was scheduled to do preparation for Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's first visit to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Albright will travel to the region next week as scheduled
despite of the Jerusalem bombing.
</P>
<P>
Erekat emphasized it is time for Palestinians and Israelis "to
join forces together to preserve the peace process and to send a
strong message to all those who are thinking seriously of
sabotaging the peace process that the only alternative for
Israelis and Palestinians is the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Countering Israel's blames that Arafat was responsible for
Thursday's suicide bombing as he had failed to crack down
terrorist groups, Erekat said, "We wish that the Israeli
government would understand that trying to assign blame will serve
no purpose."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized security coordination among the Palestinians,
Israel and the United States over the past month was making
progress and withheld massive arrests of what Israel called
terrorist suspects.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the question is whether you just go and arrest
people without any rationale for why they are arrested. I think
each name that will be arrested must have a reason for his arrest,
and we are trying to go in accordance with the rule of Palestinian
law," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had
already tried arresting hundreds of people, but had been forced to
release many of them for lack of evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
