<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Forecasts 63 Bln Dlr Surplus in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
forecast today that the budget deal between the U.S. government
and the Congress, and the continued growing U.S. economy, will
produce a budget surplus of 63 billion dollars in 2002.
</P>
<P>
That's nearly twice the size of the surplus estimated earlier
this week by the Congressional Budget Office, which forecast a
surplus of 32 billion dollars in 2002.
</P>
<P>
In a mid-year review of the economy, the White House Office of
Management and Budget said the deficit for the current fiscal
year, which ends September 30, would be 37 billion dollars, the
smallest deficit since 1974 and 90 billion lower than the White
House initially estimated.
</P>
<P>
The administration predicted that the surpluses would rise at
least through 2007.
</P>
<P>
The projected 63-billion-dollar surplus in 2002 would be the
first balanced budget since 1969.
</P>
<P>
The report asserted that, without the balanced-budget accord
reached between the U.S. government and the Congress in July, the
deficit would have begun to rise in 1998 and remain between 50
billion and 100 billion dollars for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
In other forecasts, the Clinton administration said inflation,
as measured by the Consumer Price Index, would be 2.4 percent this
year and 2.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
It said that economic growth, as measured by changes in the
gross domestic product, would be 3.5 percent for this year and
then range from 2 percent to 2.4 percent over the next five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
