<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US House Backs Putting Troops on Border With Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives today voted for its support for deploying up to
10,000 troops to guard the border with Mexico to keep out drugs
and illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The measure, proposed by Republican Jim Traficant, was approved
by a vote of 261-150. Under the bill, the troops could render aid
to the border patrol and immigration authorities in inspections
and detaining illegal aliens
</P>
<P>
However, troops would be barred from making arrests and other
civilian law enforcement activities. They would be deployed only
if the attorney general requested the aid and the Pentagon agreed.
</P>
<P>
The effort is aiming at ensuring that the negotiators writing
the final version of next year's defense bill include the troop
measure.
</P>
<P>
But the measure is opposed by the Defense Department and the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon says such a deployment could cost 650 million U.S.
dollars while the Justice Department warned of problems when
troops trained for combat are deployed on covert drug surveillance
missions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
